# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ernst-cloos
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Waters was born as the youngest of seven children of parents who were pioneers in Washington state and grew wheat at their homestead.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] He graduated in geology from the University of Washington with a B.Sc. in 1927 and an M.Sc. in 1928.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] He graduated with a Ph.D. in geology in 1930 from Yale University.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] His doctoral dissertation *Geology of the Southern Half of the Chelan [30′] Quadrangle, Washington* was supervised by Adolph Knopf.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] From 1930 to 1951 Waters held an appointment as a faculty member at Stanford University.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] He was leave of absence for the arcademic year 1937–1938 and during WW II from 1942 to 1945.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] For the academic year 1937–1938 he was a Guggenheim Fellow and did research in Scotland and Scandinavia.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] In 1940 he married Elizabeth von Hoene, who was then a student at Mills College.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] During their marriage, she often accompanied him in his fieldwork and served as camp cook.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] After the attack on Pearl Harbor, the United States Geological Survey (USGS) expanded its search for strategic minerals.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Waters went on an extended leave of absence to serve in the USGS — the main focus of his work was on mercury deposits.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] He first worked in Arkansas and then in several western states.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Before the end of WW II he was sent to search for other metal ores in different parts of the USA.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] In 1945 he returned to his professorial duties at Stanford and began to focus on basalts and other volcanic rocks of the Pacific Northwest.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Waters, in collaboration with James Gilluly and Alfred Woodford, wrote a textbook *Principles of Geology*, which was published by W.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] The *Principles of Geology* went through 4 editions and for more than two decades remained the leading introductory textbook for geology.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Waters acquired expertise concerning uranium ores and from 1951 to 1952 participated in the USGS's exploration for uranium ores on the Colorado Plateau.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] In 1952 Waters resigned from Stanford University to accept an appointment at Johns Hopkins University, where he was a professor from 1952 to 1963.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] From 1963 to 1967 he was a professor and chair of the geology department at the University of California, Santa Barbara.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] From 1967 to 1972 he was a professor at the University of California, Santa Cruz.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] There he established a Ph.D. program in earth sciences and retired as professor emeritus in 1972.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Santa Cruz, he worked with Richard Virgil Fisher on maar volcanism.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] In retirement as professor emeritus, Waters occasionally taught part-time at the University of Satan Cruz and held visiting professorships at Oregon State University, the University of Texas at El Paso, and California State University, Los Angeles.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] As professor emeritus, he also worked as a research consultant for the USGS and Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Waters was elected in 1964 a Member of the National Academy of Sciences and in 1966 a Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] In 1982 he was awarded the Penrose Medal of the Geological Society of America.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] In 1983 Aaron and Elizabeth Waters settled in Tacoma, where he continued to write about geology and pursue his hobby of gardening.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Upon his death in 1991, he was survived by his widow, their two daughters, and three grandchildren.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Waters was a leading expert on the geology of the Pacific Northwest.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] He did research on volcanology, igneous and metamorphic petrology, geomorphology, and tectonics.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Krauskopf, he did important fieldwork on protoplastic deformation found in the Colville batholith.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] Waters was the author or co-author of classic articles on determining the directions of flow in volcanic rocks and on documenting the characteristics of volcanic base surge deposits.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] As a participant in the Apollo program, he contributed to research on lunar geology, including composition and origin of the lunar surface and assessment of Apollo landing sites.
[src:ernst-cloos/aaron-c-waters] He was involved in the geological training of the astronauts, including those astronauts who later made lunar landings.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The **American Philosophical Society** (**APS**) is an American scholarly organization and learned society founded in 1743 in Philadelphia that promotes knowledge in the humanities and natural sciences through research, professional meetings, publications, library resources, and community outreach.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] It was founded by the polymath Benjamin Franklin and is considered the first learned society founded in what became the United States.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, the society's headquarters and a museum, is located just east of Independence Hall in Independence National Historical Park.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] In 1965, in recognition of the building's history, it was designated a National Historic Landmark.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The society has about 1,000 elected members.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] As of April 2020, 5,710 members had been inducted since its creation.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Through research grants, published journals, the American Philosophical Society Museum, an extensive library, and regular meetings, the society supports a variety of disciplines in the humanities and the sciences.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The American Philosophical Society was founded as the **Philosophical Society** in 1743 by Benjamin Franklin, James Alexander, Francis Hopkinson, John Bartram, Philip Syng Jr., and others as an offshoot of an earlier club, the Junto.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] It was common at the time for intellectual societies to invite members from around the world, where the society recruited members from other countries, including Alexander von Humboldt, the Marquis de Lafayette, Baron von Steuben, Tadeusz Kościuszko, and Princess Dashkova.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The society lapsed into inactivity by 1746, but was revived in 1767.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] On January 2, 1769, the society united with the American Society for Promoting Useful Knowledge under the name **American Philosophical Society Held at Philadelphia for Promoting Useful Knowledge**.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Franklin was elected the first president.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] During this time, the society maintained a standing Committee on American Improvements; one of its investigations was to study the prospects for a canal to connect the Chesapeake Bay and the Delaware River.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The Chesapeake and Delaware Canal, which had been proposed by Thomas Gilpin, Sr., was built in the 1820s.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Following the American Revolutionary War, the society looked for leadership to Francis Hopkinson, one of the signatories of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Under his influence, the society received land from the government of Pennsylvania, along with a plot of land in Philadelphia, where Philosophical Hall now stands.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Charles Darwin, Robert Frost, Louis Pasteur, Elizabeth Cabot Agassiz, John James Audubon, Linus Pauling, Margaret Mead, Woodrow Wilson, Maria Mitchell, and Thomas Edison were all prominent members of the society.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Many members of the Society of the Cincinnati were among the APS's first board members and contributors; the APS and SOC still maintain an informal, collegial relationship.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Membership of the APS "honors extraordinary accomplishments in all fields." It has about 1,000 elected members, comprising about 840 "resident" members (United States citizens or those working or living in the United States) and about 160 "international" members.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] As of February 2025 it had elected 5,890 members since its foundation.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Over that history, 220 members have been from Harvard University, 117 from Princeton University, 91 from Stanford University, and 86 from the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] In 1786, the society established the Magellanic Premium, a prize for achievement in "navigation, astronomy, or natural philosophy," the oldest scientific prize awarded by an American institution, which it still awards.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The society has published the *Transactions of the American Philosophical Society* since 1771.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The *Proceedings* have appeared since 1838; they publish the papers delivered at the society's biannual meetings.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The society has also published *The Papers of Benjamin Franklin*, Joseph Henry, William Penn, and Meriwether Lewis, and William Clark.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Jane Aitken bound 400 volumes for the society.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The society also has an expansive archive on framer of the U.S. constitution John Dickinson.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] APS holds the ACLS Collection (American Council of Learned Societies Committee on Native American Languages, American Philosophical Society) which is a collection of indigenous language documents from around the United States including recordings of the Odawa language from northern Michigan.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] APS has created a guide to help provide broad coverage of the Native American and Indigenous archival collections at the Library & Museum of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] These materials date from 1553 to 2020 and include manuscript, audio, and visual materials relating to Indigenous peoples throughout the Americas.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The society also has a collection of manuscripts on the history of the British colonies, Revolutionary War, the history of American science, quantum physics, Charles Darwin and evolution, genetics and the history of technology.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Philosophical Hall, at 104 South Fifth Street, Philadelphia, between Chestnut and Walnut Streets, immediately south of Old City Hall, was built in 1785–1789 to house the society and designed by Samuel Vaughan in the Federal style.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] A third floor was added in 1890 to accommodate the expanding library, but was removed in 1948–1950, when the building was restored to its original appearance for the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] In 2001, it was opened to the public as The American Philosophical Society Museum, hosting revolving, thematic exhibitions that explore intersections of history, art, and science.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The museum features works of art, scientific instruments, original manuscripts, rare books, natural history specimens, and curiosities of all kinds from the APS's own collections, along with objects on loan from other institutions.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] In 1789–90, the Library Company of Philadelphia (LCP)—now located at 1314 Locust Street, Philadelphia—built its headquarters, Library Hall, directly across 5th Street from APS.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] In 1884, LCP sold its building, which was demolished for the expansion of the Drexel & Company Building in 1887.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] The bank building was itself demolished in the 1950s, during the creation of Independence National Historical Park.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] In 1958, APS built a new library building on the site, that recreated the façade of LCP's Library Hall.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] APS restored the former Farmers' & Mechanics' Bank building at 425–29 Chestnut Street, which was built in 1854–55 to the design of John M.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Gries in the Italianate style, to serve as a lecture hall.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] It is the site of meetings and most major events the society hosts.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] Richardson Hall at 431 Chestnut Street, immediately west of Benjamin Franklin Hall, is the former Pennsylvania Company for Insurances on Lives and Granting Annuities Building, which was built between 1871 and 1873 and designed by Addison Hutton.
[src:ernst-cloos/american-philosophical-society] It contains offices and the Consortium for History of Science, Technology and Medicine.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The **Appalachian Mountains**, often called the **Appalachians**, are a mountain range in eastern to northeastern North America.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The term "Appalachian" refers to several different regions and mountain systems associated with the mountain range, and its surrounding terrain.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The general definition used is one followed by the United States Geological Survey and the Geological Survey of Canada to describe the respective countries' physiographic regions.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The U.S. uses the term Appalachian Highlands and Canada uses the term Appalachian Uplands; the Appalachian Mountains are not synonymous with the Appalachian Plateau, which is one of the seven provinces of the Appalachian Highlands.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The highest peak of the mountain range is Mount Mitchell in North Carolina at 6,684 feet (2,037 m), which is also the highest point in the United States east of the Mississippi River.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The range is older than the other major mountain range in North America, the Rocky Mountains of the west.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Some of the outcrops in the Appalachians contain rocks formed during the Precambrian.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The geologic processes that led to the formation of the Appalachian Mountains started 1.1 billion years ago.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The first mountain range in the region was created when the continents of Laurentia and Amazonia collided, creating a supercontinent called Rodinia.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The collision of these continents caused the rocks to be folded and faulted, creating the first mountains in the region.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Many of the rocks and minerals that were formed during that event can currently be seen at the surface of the present Appalachian range.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Around 480 million years ago, geologic processes began that led to three distinct orogenic eras that created much of the surface structure seen in today's Appalachians.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] During this period, mountains once reached elevations similar to those of the Alps and the Rockies before natural erosion occurred over the last 240 million years leading to what is present today.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Mountains are a barrier to east–west travel, as they form a series of alternating ridgelines and valleys oriented in opposition to most highways and railroads running east–west.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] This barrier was extremely important in shaping the expansion of the United States in the colonial era.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The range is the home of a very popular recreational feature, the Appalachian Trail.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] This is a 2,175-mile (3,500 km) hiking trail that runs all the way from Mount Katahdin in Maine to Springer Mountain in Georgia, passing over or past a large part of the Appalachian range.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The International Appalachian Trail is an extension of this hiking trail into the Canadian portion of the Appalachian range in New Brunswick and Quebec.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The name was soon altered by the Spanish to Apalachee and used as a name for the tribe and region spreading well inland to the north.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Pánfilo de Narváez's expedition first entered Apalachee territory on June 15, 1528, and applied the name.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Now spelled "Appalachian", it is the fourth-oldest surviving European place-name in the US.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] After the 1540 expedition of Hernando de Soto, Spanish cartographers began to apply the name of the tribe to the mountains themselves.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The first cartographic appearance of *Apalchen* is on Diego Gutiérrez's map of 1562; the first use for the mountain range is the map of Jacques le Moyne de Morgues in 1565.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The name was not commonly used for the whole mountain range until the late 19th century.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] A competing and often more popular name was the "Allegheny Mountains", "Alleghenies", and even "Alleghania".
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In the early 19th century, Washington Irving proposed renaming the United States either Appalachia or Alleghania.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In U.S. dialects in most regions of the Appalachians, the word is pronounced /ˌæpəˈlætʃɪnz/, with the third syllable sounding like "latch".
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In some northern parts of the mountain range, particularly Pennsylvania, it is pronounced /ˌæpəˈleɪtʃɪnz/ or /ˌæpəˈleɪʃɪnz/; the third syllable is like "lay", and the fourth "chins" or "shins".
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] There is often great debate between the residents of the regions regarding the correct pronunciation.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Elsewhere, a commonly accepted pronunciation for the adjective *Appalachian* is /ˌæpəˈlætʃiən/, with the last two syllables "-ian" pronounced as in the word "Romanian".
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] However, each of the governments has an agency that informs the public about the major landforms that make up the countries, the United States Geological Survey (USGS) and the Geological Survey of Canada (GSC).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The landforms are referred to as physiographic regions.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The regions create precise boundaries from which maps can be drawn.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Highlands is the name of one of the eight physiographic regions of the contiguous 48 United States.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Uplands is the name of one of seven physiographic regions of Canada.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The second level in the physiographic classification schema for the USGS is "province", the same word as Canada uses to divide its political subdivisions, meaning that the terminology used by the two countries do not match below the region level.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The lowest level of classification is "section".
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Uplands are one of the seven physiographic divisions in Canada.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Canada's GSC does not use the same classification system as the USGS below the division level.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The agency does break the divisions of the Appalachian Uplands into 13 subsections that are in four different political provinces of Canada.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] While the Appalachian Highlands and Appalachian Uplands are generally continuous across the U.S./Canadian border, the St.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Lawrence Valley area is handled differently in the physiographic classification schemas.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Lawrence Valley in the United States is one of the second-level classifications, part of the Appalachian Highlands.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In Canada, the area is part of the first-level classification, the St.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] This includes the area around the city of Montreal, Anticosti Island, and the northwest coastline of Newfoundland.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The dissected plateau area, while not actually made up of geological mountains, is popularly called "mountains", especially in eastern Kentucky and West Virginia, and while the ridges are not high, the terrain is extremely rugged.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In Ohio and New York, some of the plateau has been glaciated, which has rounded off the sharp ridges and filled the valleys to some extent.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The glaciated regions are usually referred to as hill country rather than mountains.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The mountain system has no axis of dominating altitudes, but in every portion, the summits rise to rather uniform heights, and, especially in the central section, the various ridges and intermontane valleys have the same trend as the system itself.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] None of the summits reaches the region of perpetual snow.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In Pennsylvania, there are over sixty summits that rise over 2,500 ft (800 m); the summits of Mount Davis and Blue Knob rise over 3,000 ft (900 m).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In Maryland, Eagle Rock and Dans Mountain are conspicuous points reaching 3,162 and 2,882 ft (964 and 878 m) respectively.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] On the same side of the Great Valley, south of the Potomac, are the Pinnacle 3,007 feet (917 m) and Pidgeon Roost 3,400 ft (1,000 m).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In West Virginia, more than 150 peaks rise above 4,000 ft (1,200 m), including Spruce Knob 4,863 ft (1,482 m), the highest point in the Allegheny Mountains.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] A number of other points in the state rise above 4,800 ft (1,500 m).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Cheat Mountain (Snowshoe Mountain) at Thorny Flat 4,848 ft (1,478 m) and Bald Knob 4,842 ft (1,476 m) are among the more notable peaks in West Virginia.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Blue Ridge Mountains, rising in southern Pennsylvania and there known as South Mountain, attain elevations of about 2,000 ft (600 m) in Pennsylvania.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] South Mountain achieves its highest point just below the Mason-Dixon line in Maryland at Quirauk Mountain 2,145 ft (654 m) and then diminishes in height southward to the Potomac River.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Once in Virginia, the Blue Ridge again reaches 2,000 ft (600 m) and higher.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In the Virginia Blue Ridge, the following are some of the highest peaks north of the Roanoke River: Stony Man 4,031 ft (1,229 m), Hawksbill Mountain 4,066 ft (1,239 m), Apple Orchard Mountain 4,225 ft (1,288 m) and Peaks of Otter 4,001 and 3,875 ft (1,220 and 1,181 m).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] South of the Roanoke River, along the Blue Ridge, are Virginia's highest peaks including Whitetop Mountain 5,520 ft (1,680 m) and Mount Rogers 5,729 ft (1,746 m), the highest point in the Commonwealth.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Chief summits in the southern section of the Blue Ridge are located along two main crests, the Western or Unaka Front along the Tennessee-North Carolina border and the Eastern Front in North Carolina, or one of several "cross ridges" between the two main crests.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Prominent summits in the cross ridges include Waterrock Knob (6,292 ft (1,918 m)) in the Plott Balsams.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Across northern Georgia, numerous peaks exceed 4,000 ft (1,200 m), including Brasstown Bald, the state's highest, at 4,784-and-4,696 ft (1,458-and-1,431 m) Rabun Bald.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In north-central Alabama, Mount Cheaha rises prominently to 1,445 feet (440 m) over its surroundings, as part of the southernmost spur of the Blue Ridge Mountains.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Plate tectonics over the period dating back at least 1 billion years led to geological creation of the land that is now the Appalachian Mountain range.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The continental movement led to collisions that built mountains and they later pulled apart creating oceans over parts of the continent that are now exposed.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The first mountain-building tectonic plate collision that initiated the construction of what are today the Appalachians occurred at least a billion years ago when the pre-North American craton called Laurentia collided with at least one other craton — Amazonia.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] All the other cratons of the earth also collided at about this time to form the supercontinent Rodinia and were surrounded by one single ocean.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] (It is possible that the cratons of Kalahari, and Rio Plato, were also part of that early collision since they were present as Rodinia broke up).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Mountain-building referred to as the Grenville Orogeny occurred along the boundaries of the cratons.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The present Appalachian Mountains have at least two areas which are made from rock formations that were formed during this orogeny - the Blue Ridge Mountains and the Adirondacks.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] After the Grenville orogeny, the direction of the continental drift reversed, and the single supercontinent Rodinia began to break up.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The mountains formed during the Grenvillian era underwent erosion due to weathering, glaciation, and other natural processes, resulting in the leveling of the landscape.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The eroded sediments from these mountains contributed to the formation of sedimentary basins and valleys.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] For example, in what is now the southern United States, the Ococee Basin was formed.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Rivers from the surrounding countryside carried clay, silt, sand, and gravel to the basin, much as rivers today carry sediment from the midcontinent region to the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The sediment spread out in layers on the basin floor.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The basin continued to subside, and over a long period of time, probably millions of years, a great thickness of sediment accumulated.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Eventually, the tectonic forces pulling the two continents apart became so strong that an ocean formed off the eastern coast of the Laurentian margin.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] This was called the Iapetus Ocean and was the precursor of the modern Atlantic Ocean.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The rocks of the Valley and Ridge province formed over millions of years, in the Iapetus.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Shells and other hard parts of ancient marine plants and animals accumulated to form limey deposits that later became limestone.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] This is the same process by which limestone forms in modern oceans.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The weathering of limestone, now exposed at the land surface, produces the lime-rich soils that are so prevalent in the fertile farmland of the Valley and Ridge province.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] During this continental break-up, around 600 million to 560 million years ago, volcanic activity was present along the tectonic margins.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] There is evidence of this activity in today's Blue Ridge Mountains.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Mount Rogers, Whitetop Mountain, and Pine Mountain are all the result of volcanic activity that occurred around this time.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Evidence of subsurface activity, dikes and sills intruding into the overlying rock, is present in the Blue Ridge as well.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] For instance, mafic rocks have been found along the Fries Fault in the central Blue Ridge area of Montgomery County, Virginia.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] One of the best examples of mafic rocks from the breakup of Rodina is the Catoctin Formation.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Erupted during the final stages of rifting associated with Rodinia (570-550 Ma), these rocks where later metamorphosed into Greenstone.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Iapetus continued to expand and during that time bacteria, algae, and many species of invertebrates flourished in the oceans, but there were no plants or animals on land.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Then, during the middle Ordovician Period about 500 to 470 million years ago, the motion of the crustal plates changed, and the continents began to move back toward each other.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The once-quiet Appalachian passive margin changed to a very active plate boundary when a neighboring Iapetus oceanic plate containing a volcanic arc collided with and began sinking beneath the North American craton.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Volcanoes grew along the continental margin coincident with the initiation of subduction.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Thrust faulting uplifted and warped older sedimentary rock laid down on the passive margin.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] As the mountains rose, erosion began to wear them down over time.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Streams carried rock debris downslope to be deposited in nearby lowlands.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Taconic orogeny ended after about 60 million years, but built much of the land mass that is now New England and southwestward to Pennsylvania.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Taconic Orogeny was the second of four mountain building plate collisions that contributed to the formation of the Appalachians, culminating in the collision of North America and Africa (see Alleghanian orogeny).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The third mountain-building event was the Acadian orogeny which occurred between 375 and 359 million years ago.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Acadian orogeny was caused by a series of collisions of pieces of crust from the Avalonia Terrane, sections broken off from continent of Gondwana, with the North American Plate.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The collision initiating this orogeny resulted in the closing of the southern Iapetus Ocean and the formation of a high mountain belt.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] After the Acadian collision took place, Gondwana began to retreat from Laurentia with the newly accreted Avalonian terranes left behind.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] As Gondwana moved away, a new ocean opened up, the Rheic Ocean, during the Middle to Late Devonian, and subsequently its closure would result in the formation of the Alleghanian orogeny.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] As the continental plates moved closer together, fragments of oceanic crust, islands, and other continental masses collided with the eastern margin of ancestral North America.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] By this time, plants had appeared on land, followed by scorpions, insects, and amphibians.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The ocean continued to shrink until, about 270 million years ago, the continents that were ancestral to North America and Africa collided during the formation of the supercontinent Pangea.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Because North America and Africa were once geographically connected, the Appalachians formed part of the same mountain chain as the Little Atlas in Morocco.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] This mountain range, known as the Central Pangean Mountains, extended into Scotland, before the Mesozoic Era opening of the Iapetus Ocean, from the North America/Europe collision (See Caledonian orogeny).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] By the end of the Mesozoic Era, the Appalachian Mountains had been eroded to an almost flat plain.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] It was not until the region was uplifted during the Cenozoic Era that the distinctive topography of the present formed.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Uplift rejuvenated the streams, which rapidly responded by cutting downward into the ancient bedrock.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Some streams flowed along weak layers that define the folds and faults created many millions of years earlier.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Other streams downcut so rapidly that they cut right across the resistant folded rocks of the mountain core, carving canyons across rock layers and geologic structures.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian Mountains contain major deposits of anthracite coal as well as bituminous coal.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In the folded mountains the coal is in metamorphosed form as anthracite, represented by the Coal Region of northeastern Pennsylvania.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The bituminous coal fields of western Pennsylvania, western Maryland, southeastern Ohio, eastern Kentucky, southwestern Virginia, and West Virginia contain the sedimentary form of coal.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The mountain top removal method of coal mining, in which entire mountain tops are removed, is currently threatening vast areas and ecosystems of the Appalachian Mountain region.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The surface coal mining that started in the 1940s has significantly impacted the central Appalachian Mountains in Kentucky, Tennessee, Virginia and West Virginia.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Early mining methods were unregulated and mined land reclamation research, including acid base accounting, was led by the West Virginia University in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] West Virginia developed rigorous mine reclamation standards for state coal mines in the late 1960s.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Regulations were introduced by most states to protect the Appalachian Mountains by the late 1960s.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Social and political activism brought about the Surface Mining Control and Reclamation Act of 1977.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The 1859 discovery of commercial quantities of petroleum in the Appalachian Mountains of western Pennsylvania started the modern United States petroleum industry.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Recent discoveries of commercial natural gas deposits in the Marcellus Shale formation and Utica Shale formations have once again focused oil industry attention on the Appalachian Basin.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Some plateaus of the Appalachian Mountains contain metallic minerals such as iron and zinc.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] There are many geological issues concerning the rivers and streams of the Appalachians.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In spite of the existence of the Great Appalachian Valley, many of the main rivers are transverse to the mountain system axis.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The drainage divide of the Appalachians follows a tortuous course that crosses the mountainous belt just north of the New River in Virginia.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In the northern section, the height of land lies on the inland side of the mountainous belt, and thus the main lines of drainage run from north to south, exemplified by the Hudson River.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] However, the valley through which the Hudson River flows was cut by the gigantic glaciers of the ice ages—the same glaciers that deposited their terminal moraines in southern New York and formed the east–west Long Island.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian region is generally considered the geographical divide between the eastern seaboard of the United States and the Midwest region of the country.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Eastern Continental Divide follows the Appalachian Mountains from Pennsylvania to Georgia.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachians, particularly the Central and Southern regions, is one of the most biodiverse places in North America.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The north–south orientation of the long ridges and valleys contributes to the high number of plant and animal species.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Species were able to migrate through these from either direction during alternating periods of warming and cooling, settling in the microclimates that best suited them.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The flora of the Appalachians are diverse and vary primarily in response to geology, latitude, elevation and moisture availability.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Geobotanically, they constitute a floristic province of the North American Atlantic Region.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachians consist primarily of deciduous broad-leaf trees and evergreen needle-leaf conifers, but also contain the evergreen broad-leaf American holly (*Ilex opaca*), and the deciduous needle-leaf conifer, the tamarack, or eastern larch (*Larix laricina*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The dominant northern and high elevation conifer is the red spruce (*Picea rubens*), which grows from near sea level to above 4,000 ft (1,200 m) above sea level (asl) in northern New England and southeastern Canada.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] It also grows southward along the Appalachian crest to the highest elevations of the southern Appalachians, as in North Carolina and Tennessee.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In the central Appalachians it is usually confined above 3,000 ft (900 m) asl, except for a few cold valleys in which it reaches lower elevations.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In the southern Appalachians, it is restricted to higher elevations.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Another species is the black spruce (*Picea mariana*), which extends farthest north of any conifer in North America, is found at high elevations in the northern Appalachians, and in bogs as far south as Pennsylvania.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachians are also home to two species of fir, the boreal balsam fir (*Abies balsamea*), and the southern high elevation endemic, Fraser fir (*Abies fraseri*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Fraser fir is endemic to the highest parts of the southern Appalachian Mountains, where along with red spruce it forms a fragile ecosystem known as the Southern Appalachian spruce–fir forest.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Fraser fir rarely occurs below 5,500 ft (1,700 m), and becomes the dominant tree type at 6,200 ft (1,900 m).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] By contrast, balsam fir is found from near sea level to the tree line in the northern Appalachians, but ranges only as far south as Virginia and West Virginia in the central Appalachians, where it is usually confined above 3,900 ft (1,200 m) asl, except in cold valleys.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Curiously, it is associated with oaks in Virginia.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The balsam fir of Virginia and West Virginia is thought by some to be a natural hybrid between the more northern variety and Fraser fir.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] While red spruce is common in both upland and bog habitats, balsam fir, as well as black spruce and tamarack, are more characteristic of the latter.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] However, balsam fir also does well in soils with a pH as high as 6.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Eastern or Canada hemlock (*Tsuga canadensis*) is another important evergreen needle-leaf conifer that grows along the Appalachian chain from north to south but is confined to lower elevations than red spruce and the firs.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] It generally occupies richer and less acidic soils than the spruce and firs and is characteristic of deep, shaded and moist mountain valleys and coves.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] It is subject to the hemlock woolly adelgid (*Adelges tsugae*), an introduced insect, that is rapidly extirpating it as a forest tree.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Less abundant, and restricted to the southern Appalachians, is Carolina hemlock (*Tsuga caroliniana*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Like Canada hemlock, this tree suffers severely from the hemlock woolly adelgid.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Several species of pines characteristic of the Appalachians are eastern white pine (*Pinus strobus*), Virginia pine (*Pinus virginiana*), pitch pine (*Pinus rigida*), Table Mountain pine (*Pinus pungens*) and shortleaf pine (*Pinus echinata*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Red pine (*Pinus resinosa*) is a boreal species that forms a few high elevation outliers as far south as West Virginia.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] All of these species except white pine tend to occupy sandy, rocky, poor soil sites, which are mostly acidic in character.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] White pine, a large species valued for its timber, tends to do best in rich, moist soil, either acidic or alkaline in character.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Pitch pine is also at home in acidic, boggy soil, and Table Mountain pine may occasionally be found in this habitat as well.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Shortleaf pine is generally found in warmer habitats and at lower elevations than the other species.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] All the species listed do best in open or lightly shaded habitats, although white pine also thrives in shady coves, valleys, and on floodplains.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachians are characterized by a wealth of large, beautiful deciduous broadleaf (hardwood) trees.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Their occurrences are best summarized and described in E.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Lucy Braun's 1950 classic, *Deciduous Forests of Eastern North America* (Macmillan, New York).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The most diverse and richest forests are the mixed-mesophytic or medium-moisture types, which are largely confined to rich, moist montane soils of the southern and central Appalachians, particularly in the Cumberland and Allegheny Mountains, but also thrive in the southern Appalachian coves.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Characteristic canopy species are white basswood (*Tilia heterophylla*), yellow buckeye (*Aesculus octandra*), sugar maple (*Acer saccharum*), American beech (*Fagus grandifolia*), tuliptree (*Liriodendron tulipifera*), white ash (*Fraxinus americana*) and yellow birch (*Betula alleganiensis*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Other common trees are red maple (*Acer rubrum*), shagbark and bitternut hickories (*Carya ovata* and *C. cordiformis*) and black or sweet birch (*Betula lenta*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Small understory trees and shrubs include paw paw (*Asimina tribola*), flowering dogwood (*Cornus florida*), hophornbeam (*Ostrya virginiana*), witch-hazel (*Hamamelis virginiana*) and spicebush (*Lindera benzoin*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] There are also hundreds of perennial and annual herbs, among them such herbal and medicinal plants as American ginseng (*Panax quinquefolius*), goldenseal (*Hydrastis canadensis*), bloodroot (*Sanguinaria canadensis*) and black cohosh (*Cimicifuga racemosa*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The foregoing trees, shrubs, and herbs are also more widely distributed in less rich mesic forests that generally occupy coves, stream valleys and flood plains throughout the southern and central Appalachians at low and intermediate elevations.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Drier and rockier uplands and ridges are occupied by oak–chestnut forests dominated by a variety of oaks (*Quercus* spp.), hickories (*Carya* spp.) and, in the past, by the American chestnut (*Castanea dentata*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The American chestnut was virtually eliminated as a canopy species by the introduced fungal chestnut blight (*Cryphonectaria parasitica*), but lives on as sapling-sized sprouts that originate from roots, which are not killed by the fungus.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In present-day forest canopies, chestnut has been largely replaced by oaks.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The oak forests of the southern and central Appalachians consist largely of black, northern red, white, chestnut and scarlet oaks (*Quercus velutina*, *Q. rubra*, *Q. alba*, *Q. prinus* and *Q. coccinea*) and hickories, such as the pignut (*Carya glabra*) in particular.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The richest forests, which grade into mesic types, usually in coves and on gentle slopes, have predominantly white and northern red oaks, while the driest sites are dominated by chestnut oak, or sometimes by scarlet or northern red oaks.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In the northern Appalachians the oaks, except for white and northern red, drop out, while the latter extends farthest north.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The oak forests generally lack the diverse small tree, shrub and herb layers of mesic forests.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The evergreen great rhododendron (*Rhododendron maximum*) is characteristic of moist stream valleys.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] These occurrences are in line with the prevailing acidic character of most oak forest soils.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In contrast, the much rarer chinquapin oak (*Quercus muehlenbergii*) demands alkaline soils and generally grows where limestone rock is near the surface.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Hence no ericaceous shrubs are associated with it.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The Appalachian flora also include a diverse assemblage of bryophytes (mosses and liverworts), as well as fungi.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] As with vascular plants, these tend to be closely related to the character of the soils and the thermal environment in which they are found.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Eastern deciduous forests are subject to a number of serious insect and disease outbreaks.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Among the most conspicuous is that of the introduced spongy moth (*Lymantria dispar*), which infests primarily oaks, causing severe defoliation and tree mortality.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] But it also has the benefit of eliminating weak individuals, and thus improving the genetic stock, as well as creating rich habitat of a type through accumulation of dead wood.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Because hardwoods sprout so readily, this moth is not as harmful as the hemlock woolly adelgid.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Perhaps more serious is the introduced beech bark disease complex, which includes both a scale insect (*Cryptococcus fagisuga*) and fungal components.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] During the 19th and early 20th centuries, the Appalachian forests were subject to severe and destructive logging and land clearing, which resulted in the designation of the national forests and parks as well many state-protected areas.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] However, these and a variety of other destructive activities continue, albeit in diminished forms; and thus far only a few ecologically based management practices have taken hold.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Appalachian bogs are boreal ecosystems, which occur in many places in the Appalachians, particularly the Allegheny and Blue Ridge subranges.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Though popularly called bogs, many of them are technically fens.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Several mountain summits in the southern Appalachians are covered with expansive open habitats (either grassy meadows or heath) known as Appalachian balds.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] These habitats support many unique plant and animal communities, including rare, relict species, that are adapted to the open, exposed habitat.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Others, especially those dominated by introduced grasses, may be fully anthropogenic in origin.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The abandonment of grazing has caused trees to encroach on many of these balds, threatening their ecosystems.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Animals that characterize the Appalachian forests include five species of tree squirrels.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The most commonly seen is the low to moderate elevation eastern gray squirrel (*Sciurus carolinensis*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Occupying similar habitat is the slightly larger fox squirrel (*Sciurus niger*) and the much smaller southern flying squirrel (*Glaucomys volans*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] As familiar as squirrels are the eastern cottontail rabbit (*Silvilagus floridanus*) and the white-tailed deer (*Odocoileus virginianus*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The latter in particular has greatly increased in abundance as a result of the extirpation of the eastern wolf (*Canis lupus lycaon*) and the North American cougar.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] This has led to the overgrazing and browsing of many plants of the Appalachian forests, as well as destruction of agricultural crops.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Other deer include the moose (*Alces alces*), found only in the north, and the elk (*Cervus canadensis*), which, although once extirpated, is now making a comeback, through transplantation, in the southern and central Appalachians.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] In Quebec, the Chic-Chocs host the only population of reindeer (*Rangifer tarandus*) south of the St.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] An additional species that is common in the north but extends its range southward at high elevations to Virginia and West Virginia is the varying or snowshoe hare (*Lepus americanus*).
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] However, these central Appalachian populations are scattered and very small.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Another species of great interest is the beaver (*Castor canadensis*), which is showing a great resurgence in numbers after its near extirpation for its pelt.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] This resurgence is bringing about a drastic alteration in habitat through the construction of dams and other structures throughout the mountains.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] European boars (*Sus scrofa*) were introduced in the early 20th century.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Of great importance are the many species of salamanders and, in particular, the lungless species (family Plethodontidae) that live in great abundance concealed by leaves and debris, on the forest floor.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Most frequently seen, however, is the eastern or red-spotted newt (*Notophthalmus viridescens*), whose terrestrial eft form is often encountered on the open, dry forest floor.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] It has been estimated that salamanders represent the largest class of animal biomass in the Appalachian forests.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Frogs and toads are of lesser diversity and abundance, but the wood frog (*Rana sylvatica*) is, like the eft, commonly encountered on the dry forest floor, while a number of species of small frogs, such as spring peepers (*Pseudacris crucifer*), enliven the forest with their calls.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Salamanders and other amphibians contribute greatly to nutrient cycling through their consumption of small life forms on the forest floor and in aquatic habitats.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Although reptiles are less abundant and diverse than amphibians, a number of snakes are conspicuous members of the fauna.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] One of the largest is the non-venomous black rat snake (*Elaphe obsoleta obsoleta*), while the common garter snake (*Thamnophis sirtalis*) is among the smallest but most abundant.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The eastern copperhead (*Agkistrodon contortrix*) and the timber rattler (*Crotalus horridus*) are venomous pit vipers.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] There are few lizards, but the broad-headed skink (*Eumeces laticeps*), at up to 13 in (33 cm) in length, and an excellent climber and swimmer, is one of the largest and most spectacular in appearance and action.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] The most common turtle is the eastern box turtle (*Terrapene carolina carolina*), which is found in both upland and lowland forests in the central and southern Appalachians.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Prominent among aquatic species is the large common snapping turtle (*Chelydra serpentina*), which occurs throughout the Appalachians.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Appalachian streams are notable for their highly diverse freshwater fish life.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Among the most abundant and diverse are those of the minnow family (family Cyprinidae), while species of the colorful darters (*Percina* spp.) are also abundant.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] A characteristic fish of shaded, cool Appalachian forest streams is the wild brook or speckled trout (*Salvelinus fontinalis*), which is much sought after as a game fish.
[src:ernst-cloos/appalachian-mountains] Water Striders (family *Gerridae*) are insects commonly seen on the surface of calm streams and ponds.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The land that is present-day Baltimore was once used as hunting ground by Paleo-Indians.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In the early 1600s, the Susquehannock began to hunt there.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] People from the Province of Maryland established the Port of Baltimore in 1706 to support the tobacco trade with Europe and established the Town of Baltimore in 1729.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Battle of Baltimore was pivotal during the War of 1812, culminating in the British bombardment of Fort McHenry, during which Francis Scott Key wrote a poem that became "The Star-Spangled Banner", which was designated as the national anthem in 1931.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] During the Pratt Street Riot of 1861, the city was the site of some of the earliest violence associated with the American Civil War.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore and Ohio Railroad, the nation's oldest, was built in 1830 and reinforced Baltimore's status as a transportation hub, giving producers in the Midwest and Appalachia access to the city's port.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore's Inner Harbor was the second-leading port of entry for immigrants to the U.S. after New York's Ellis Island, making Baltimore a major manufacturing center.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] After a decline in heavy industry and restructuring of the rail industry, Baltimore has shifted to a service-oriented economy.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Johns Hopkins Hospital and University are now the city's top employers.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is also home to the Baltimore Orioles of Major League Baseball and the Baltimore Ravens of the National Football League.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] It is ranked as a Gamma− world city by the Globalization and World Cities Research Network.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The city is home to some of the earliest National Register Historic Districts in the nation, including Fell's Point, Federal Hill, and Mount Vernon.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has more public statues and monuments per capita than any other city in the U.S.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Nearly one third of the buildings (over 65,000) are designated as historic in the National Register, more than any other U.S. city.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has 66 National Register Historic Districts and 33 local historic districts.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The city is named after Cecil Calvert, 2nd Baron Baltimore, an English politician and lawyer who was a founding proprietor of the Province of Maryland.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Calverts took the title Barons Baltimore from Baltimore Manor, an estate they were granted by the Crown in County Longford as part of the plantations of Ireland.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is an anglicization of *Baile an Tí Mhóir*, meaning "town of the big house" in Irish.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore area was inhabited by Native Americans since at least the 10th millennium BC, when Paleo-Indians first settled in the region.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] One Paleo-Indian site and several Archaic period and Woodland period archaeological sites have been identified in Baltimore, including four from the Late Woodland period.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In December 2021, several Woodland period Native American artifacts were found in Herring Run Park in northeast Baltimore, dating 5,000 to 9,000 years ago.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The finding followed a period of dormancy in Baltimore City archaeological findings which had persisted since the 1980s.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] During the Late Woodland period, the archaeological culture known as the Potomac Creek complex resided in the area from Baltimore south to the Rappahannock River in present-day Virginia.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In the early 1600s, the immediate Baltimore vicinity was sparsely populated, if at all, by Native Americans.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore County area northward was used as hunting grounds by the Susquehannock living in the lower Susquehanna River valley.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] This Iroquoian-speaking people "controlled all of the upper tributaries of the Chesapeake" but "refrained from much contact with Powhatan in the Potomac region" and south into Virginia.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Pressured by the Susquehannock, the Piscataway tribe, an Algonquian-speaking people, stayed well south of the Baltimore area and inhabited primarily the north bank of the Potomac River in what are now Charles and southern Prince George's counties in the coastal areas south of the Fall Line.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] European colonization of Maryland began in earnest with the arrival of the merchant ship *The Ark* carrying 140 colonists at St.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Clement's Island in the Potomac River on March 25, 1634.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Europeans then began to settle the area further north, in what is now Baltimore County.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Since Maryland was a colony, Baltimore's streets were named to show loyalty to the mother country, e.g.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] King, Queen, King George and Caroline streets.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The original county seat, known today as Old Baltimore, was located on Bush River within the present-day Aberdeen Proving Ground.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The colonists engaged in sporadic warfare with the Susquehannock, whose numbers dwindled primarily from new infectious diseases, such as smallpox, endemic among the Europeans.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 1661, David Jones claimed the area known today as Jonestown on the east bank of the Jones Falls stream.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The colonial General Assembly of Maryland created the Port of Baltimore at old Whetstone Point, now Locust Point, in 1706 for the tobacco trade.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Town of Baltimore, on the west side of the Jones Falls, was founded on August 8, 1729, when the Governor of Maryland signed an act allowing "the building of a Town on the North side of the Patapsco River".
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Surveyors began laying out the town on January 12, 1730.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] By 1752 the town had just 27 homes, including a church and two taverns.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Jonestown and Fells Point had been settled to the east.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The three settlements, covering 60 acres (24 ha), became a commercial hub, and in 1768 were designated as the county seat.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The first printing press was introduced to the city in 1765 by Nicholas Hasselbach, whose equipment was later used in the printing of Baltimore's first newspapers, *The Maryland Journal* and *The Baltimore Advertiser*, first published by William Goddard in 1773.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore grew swiftly in the 18th century, its plantations producing grain and tobacco for sugar-producing colonies in the Caribbean.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The profit from sugar encouraged the cultivation of cane in the Caribbean and the importation of food by planters there.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Since Baltimore was the county seat, a courthouse was built in 1768 to serve both the city and county.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Its square was a center of community meetings and discussions.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore established its public market system in 1763.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Lexington Market, founded in 1782, is one of the oldest continuously operating public markets in the United States today.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Lexington Market was also a center of slave trading.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Enslaved Black people were sold at numerous sites through the downtown area, with sales advertised in *The Baltimore Sun*.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Both tobacco and sugar cane were labor-intensive crops.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 1774, Baltimore established the first post office system in what became the United States, and the first water company chartered in the newly independent nation, Baltimore Water Company, 1792.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore played a part in the American Revolution.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] City leaders such as Jonathan Plowman Jr. led many residents to resist British taxes, and merchants signed agreements refusing to trade with Britain.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Second Continental Congress met in the Henry Fite House from December 1776 to February 1777, effectively making the city the capital of the United States during this period.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore, Jonestown, and Fells Point were incorporated as the City of Baltimore in 1796–1797.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The city remained a part of surrounding Baltimore County and continued to serve as its county seat from 1768 to 1851, after which it became an independent city.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The British bombardment of Baltimore in 1814 inspired the U.S. national anthem, "The Star-Spangled Banner", and the construction of the Battle Monument, which became the city's official emblem.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] A distinctive local culture started to take shape, and a unique skyline peppered with churches and monuments developed.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore acquired its moniker "The Monumental City" after an 1827 visit to Baltimore by President John Quincy Adams.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore pioneered the use of gas lighting in 1816, and its population grew rapidly in the following decades, with concomitant development of culture and infrastructure.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The construction of the federally funded National Road, which later became part of U.S.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Route 40, and the private Baltimore and Ohio Railroad (B. & O.) made Baltimore a major shipping and manufacturing center by linking the city with major markets in the Midwest.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] By 1820 its population had reached 60,000, and its economy had shifted from its base in tobacco plantations to sawmilling, shipbuilding, and textile production.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] These industries benefited from war but successfully shifted into infrastructure development during peacetime.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore had one of the worst riots of the antebellum South in 1835, when bad investments led to the Baltimore bank riot.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] It was these riots that led to the city being nicknamed "Mobtown".
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Soon after the city created the world's first dental college, the Baltimore College of Dental Surgery, in 1840, and shared in the world's first telegraph line, between Baltimore and Washington, D.C., in 1844.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Maryland, a slave state with limited popular support for secession, especially in the three counties of Southern Maryland, remained part of the Union during the American Civil War, following the 55–12 vote by the Maryland General Assembly against secession.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In February 1861, a plot in Baltimore to assassinate President-elect Abraham Lincoln was foiled by agents of the Pinkerton National Detective Agency.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Lincoln was able to pass through the city unnoticed, and arrived in Washington to be inaugurated a little more than a week later.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Later, the Union's strategic occupation of the city in 1861 ensured Maryland would not further consider secession.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Union's capital of Washington, D.C. was well-situated to impede Baltimore and Maryland's communication or commerce with the Confederacy.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore experienced some of the first casualties of the Civil War on April 19, 1861, when Union Army soldiers en route from President Street Station to Camden Yards clashed with a secessionist mob in the Pratt Street riot.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In the midst of the Long Depression that followed the Panic of 1873, the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad company attempted to lower its workers' wages, leading to strikes and riots in the city and beyond.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Strikers clashed with the National Guard, leaving 10 dead and 25 wounded. settlement movement work in Baltimore began in 1893 with the founding of the Lawrence House on West Lombard Street.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] On February 7, 1904, the Great Baltimore Fire destroyed more than 1,500 buildings and left over 70 blocks of downtown Baltimore burned to the ground.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Damage was estimated at $150 million in 1904 dollars.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Rebuilding over the following years included improvements in firefighting equipment standards.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 1910, Baltimore enacted a residential segregation ordinance that restricted African-Americans from moving into majority-White blocks, and White residents from moving into majority-Black blocks.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] It was the first ordinance of its kind in the United States and became a model for similar laws in other southern cities, although the U.S.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Supreme Court later ruled such ordinances unconstitutional in *Buchanan v.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore expanded through annexations until 1918, when it acquired portions of Baltimore County and Anne Arundel County.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] A 1948 state constitutional amendment required a local vote in any area proposed for annexation, effectively preventing further expansion of the city's boundaries.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] During the mid-20th century, migration from the Deep South and white suburbanization changed the city's demographics: the Black share of the population rose from 23.8% in 1950 to 46.4% in 1970.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore riot of 1968 followed the assassination of Martin Luther King Jr. on April 4, 1968.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Public order was not restored until April 12, and National Guard and federal troops were sent into the city.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 1974, the city again faced major disruption when teachers, municipal workers, and police officers went on strike.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] By the early 1970s, the Inner Harbor had declined into an area of abandoned warehouses.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Redevelopment began with projects such as the Maryland Science Center in 1976, the Baltimore World Trade Center in 1977, and the Baltimore Convention Center in 1979.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Harborplace opened in 1980, followed by the National Aquarium and the Baltimore Museum of Industry in 1981.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 1992, the Baltimore Orioles moved from Memorial Stadium to Oriole Park at Camden Yards, near the Inner Harbor.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore Ravens later moved into M&T Bank Stadium, next to Camden Yards, in 1998.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has seen the reopening of the Hippodrome Theatre in 2004, the opening of the Reginald F.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Lewis Museum of Maryland African American History & Culture in 2005, and the establishment of the National Slavic Museum in 2012.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In April 2012, Johns Hopkins dedicated a $1.1 billion expansion of the Johns Hopkins Hospital, among the largest medical complexes in the United States, comprising the Sheikh Zayed Cardiovascular and Critical Care Tower and the Charlotte R.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In September 2016, the Baltimore City Council approved a $660 million bond deal for the $5.5 billion Port Covington redevelopment project championed by Under Armour founder Kevin Plank and his real estate company Sagamore Development.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Port Covington surpassed the Harbor Point development as the largest tax-increment financing deal in Baltimore's history and among the largest urban redevelopment projects in the country.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The waterfront development includes a new headquarters for Under Armour along with shops, housing, offices, and manufacturing space.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In the early hours of March 26, 2024, the city's 1.6-mile (2.6 km) Francis Scott Key Bridge, which constituted a southeast portion of the Baltimore Beltway, was struck by a container ship and completely collapsed.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] A major rescue operation was launched with US authorities attempting to rescue people in the water.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Eight construction workers, who were working on the bridge at the time, fell into the Patapsco River.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Two people were rescued from the water, and the bodies of the remaining six were all found by May 7.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Replacement of the bridge was estimated in May 2024 at a cost approaching $2 billion for a fall 2028 completion.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is in north-central Maryland on the Patapsco River, close to where it empties into the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is located on the fall line between the Piedmont Plateau and the Atlantic coastal plain, which divides Baltimore into "lower city" and "upper city".
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore's elevation ranges from sea level at the harbor to 480 feet (150 m) in the northwest corner near Pimlico.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In the 2010 census, Baltimore has a total area of 92.1 square miles (239 km2), of which 80.9 sq mi (210 km2) is land and 11.1 sq mi (29 km2) is water.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is almost entirely surrounded by Baltimore County, but is politically independent of it.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] It is bordered by Anne Arundel County to the south.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore exhibits examples from each period of architecture over more than two centuries, and work from architects such as Benjamin Latrobe, George A.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Frederick, John Russell Pope, Mies van der Rohe, and I.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is rich in architecturally significant buildings in a variety of styles.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Baltimore Basilica (1806–1821) is a neoclassical design by Benjamin Latrobe, and one of the oldest Catholic cathedrals in the United States.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 1813, Robert Cary Long Sr. built for Rembrandt Peale the first substantial structure in the United States designed expressly as a museum.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Restored, it is now the Municipal Museum of Baltimore, or popularly the Peale Museum.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Phoenix Shot Tower (1828), at 234.25 feet (71.40 m) tall, was the tallest building in the United States until the time of the Civil War, and is one of few remaining structures of its kind.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] It was constructed without the use of exterior scaffolding.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Hatfield in 1851, was the city's first iron-front building and was a model for a whole generation of downtown buildings.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Brown Memorial Presbyterian Church, built in 1870 in memory of financier George Brown, has stained glass windows by Louis Comfort Tiffany and has been called "one of the most significant buildings in this city, a treasure of art and architecture" by *Baltimore* magazine.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The 1845 Greek Revival-style Lloyd Street Synagogue is one of the oldest synagogues in the United States.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Johns Hopkins Hospital, designed by Lt.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Billings in 1876, was a considerable achievement for its day in functional arrangement and fireproofing.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Pei's World Trade Center (1977) is the tallest equilateral pentagonal building in the world at 405 feet (123 m) tall.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The streets of Baltimore are organized in a grid and spoke pattern, lined with tens of thousands of rowhouses whose mix of brick and formstone facings gives the city a distinct look; the latter was a technology patented in 1937 by Albert Knight.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] John Waters characterized formstone as "the polyester of brick".
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Developers began building entire neighborhoods of rowhouses in the mid-1790s, and the form became the dominant house type of the city early in the 19th century.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Oriole Park at Camden Yards is a Major League Baseball park, which opened in 1992 and was built as a retro style baseball park.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Along with the National Aquarium, Camden Yards have helped revive the Inner Harbor area from what once was an exclusively industrial district full of dilapidated warehouses into a bustling commercial district full of bars, restaurants, and retail establishments.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is commonly divided into nine geographic regions: North, Northeast, East, Southeast, South, Southwest, West, Northwest, and Central, each corresponding to a Baltimore Police Department district.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] I-83 and Charles Street to Hanover Street and Ritchie Highway serve as a rough east–west dividing line, while Eastern Avenue to Route 40 serves as a north–south divider; for the U.S.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Postal Service, Baltimore Street is the north–south dividing line.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] North Baltimore contains historic neighborhoods such as Govans, Roland Park, Guilford, Homeland, Hampden, Charles Village, and Mount Washington, as well as the Station North Arts and Entertainment District.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] South Baltimore and Southeast Baltimore include mixed residential, industrial, and waterfront neighborhoods such as Federal Hill, Locust Point, Fells Point, Canton, Highlandtown, Little Italy, and Greektown.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Landmarks in these areas include Fort McHenry, Patterson Park, the Highlandtown Arts District, and Johns Hopkins Bayview Medical Center.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Northeast Baltimore is largely residential and includes Morgan State University, Baltimore City College, the former site of Memorial Stadium, and Lake Montebello.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] East Baltimore includes Johns Hopkins Hospital, the Johns Hopkins University School of Medicine, and neighborhoods such as Armistead Gardens, Broadway East, Barclay, and McElderry Park.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Northwest Baltimore includes Pimlico Race Course, Sinai Hospital, the headquarters of the NAACP, and neighborhoods such as Pimlico, Mount Washington, Cheswolde, and Park Heights.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] West Baltimore includes the Old West Baltimore Historic District, historically a center of the city's Black community, as well as Coppin State University, Mondawmin Mall, and Edmondson Village.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Southwest Baltimore includes Pigtown, Carrollton Ridge, Ridgely's Delight, Leakin Park, and St.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is bordered by the following communities, all unincorporated census-designated places.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has a humid subtropical (Köppen: *Cfa*) or oceanic (Trewartha: *Doak*) climate, with hot summers, cool winters, and a summer peak to annual precipitation.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is part of USDA plant hardiness zones 7b and 8a.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Summers are hot and humid, with a daily average in July of 80.7 °F (27.1 °C) and occasional late-day thunderstorms.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Spring and autumn are mild, with spring the wettest season by number of precipitation days.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Winters range from chilly to mild, with sporadic snowfall: January has a daily average of 35.8 °F (2.1 °C), though temperatures reach 50 °F (10 °C) quite often and can occasionally drop below 20 °F (−7 °C) when Arctic air masses affect the area.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] According to *Vox*, winters are warming faster than summers.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] A southeasterly bay breeze off the Chesapeake often occurs on summer afternoons; interacting with prevailing southwesterly winds and the city's urban heat island, it can exacerbate air quality.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In late summer and early autumn, hurricanes or their remnants may cause flooding in downtown Baltimore, despite the city being far removed from the typical coastal storm surge areas.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The average seasonal snowfall is 19 inches (48 cm).
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] It varies greatly by year, with some seasons seeing only trace accumulations of snow, while others see several major Nor'easters.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Owing to lessened urban heat island (UHI) as compared to the city proper and distance from the moderating Chesapeake Bay, the outlying and inland parts of the Baltimore metro area are usually cooler, especially at night, than the city proper and the coastal towns.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Thus, in the northern and western suburbs, winter snowfall is more significant, and some areas average more than 30 in (76 cm) of snow per winter.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] It is common in winter for the rain-snow line to set up in the metro area, and freezing rain and sleet occur a few times some winters.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Like all of Maryland, Baltimore is at risk for increased impacts of climate change.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Historically, flooding has ruined houses and almost killed people, especially in lower income majority Black neighborhoods, and caused sewage backups, given the existing disrepair of Baltimore's water system.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Extreme temperatures have ranged from −7 °F (−22 °C), most recently on January 22, 1984, up to 108 °F (42 °C) on July 22, 2011.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] On average, temperatures of 100 °F (38 °C) or more occur on three days annually, 90 °F (32 °C) or more on 43 days, and there are nine days where the high fails to reach the freezing mark.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore reached a peak population of 949,708 at the 1950 U.S. census count.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In every ten-year census count since then, the city has lost population, with its 2020 census population at 585,708.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore is the most populous independent city in the United States.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2020, Baltimore lost more population than any other major city in the United States.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The population increased for the first time in decades in 2024.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Gentrification has increased since the 2000 census, primarily in East Baltimore, downtown, and Central Baltimore, with 14.8% of census tracts having had income growth and home values appreciation at a rate higher than the city overall.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Many, but not all, gentrifying neighborhoods are predominantly white areas which have seen a turnover from lower income to higher income households.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] These areas represent either expansion of existing gentrified areas, or activity around the Inner Harbor, downtown, or the Johns Hopkins Homewood campus.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In some neighborhoods in East Baltimore, the Hispanic population has increased, while both the non-Hispanic white and non-Hispanic black populations have declined.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] After New York City, Baltimore was the second city in the United States to reach a population of 100,000.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] It was the second most-populous U.S. city from 1820 to 1850, and remained among the ten largest in every census through 1980.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] After World War II, the city's population approached one million before beginning its decline after the 1950 census.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In the 2010 census, Baltimore's population was 63.7% Black, 29.6% White (the largest ancestries being German, Italian, and Irish), 2.3% Asian, and 0.4% Native American and Alaska Native.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Across races, 4.2% of the population were of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin, most commonly Salvadoran and Mexican.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] As per the 2020 census, 8.1% of residents between 2016 and 2020 were foreign born persons.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Females made up 53.4% of the population.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The median age was 35 years old, with 22.4% under 18 years old, 65.8% from 18 to 64 years old, and 11.8% 65 or older.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore has a large Caribbean American population, with the largest groups being Jamaicans and Trinidadians.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore's Jamaican community is largely centered in the Park Heights neighborhood, but generations of immigrants have also lived in Southeast Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2005, approximately 30,778 people (6.5%) identified as gay, lesbian, or bisexual.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2012, same-sex marriage in Maryland was legalized, going into effect January 1, 2013.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Between 2016 and 2020, the median household income was $52,164 and the median income per capita was $32,699, compared to the national averages of $64,994 and $35,384, respectively.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2009, the median household income was $42,241 and the median income per capita was $25,707, compared to the national median income of $53,889 per household and $28,930 per capita.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2009, 23.7% of the population lived below the poverty line, compared to 13.5% nationwide.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In the 2020 census, 20% of Baltimore residents were living in poverty, compared to 11.6% nationwide.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Housing in Baltimore is relatively inexpensive for large, near-coastal cities of its size.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The median sale price for homes in Baltimore as of December 2022 was $209,000, up from $95,000 in 2012.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Despite the late 2000s housing price collapse, and along with the national trends, Baltimore residents still faced slowly increasing rent, up 3% in the summer of 2010.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The median value of owner-occupied housing units between 2016 and 2020 was $242,499.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The homeless population in Baltimore is steadily increasing.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The increase in the number of young homeless people was particularly severe.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2015, the life expectancy in Baltimore was 74 to 75 years, compared to the U.S. average of 78 to 80.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Fourteen neighborhoods, concentrated in East, West, and South Baltimore, had lower life expectancies than North Korea, and the figure in Seton Hill was comparable to that of Yemen.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2015, 25% of adults in Baltimore reported affiliation with no religion.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] 50% of the adult population of Baltimore are Protestants.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Catholicism is the second-largest religious affiliation, constituting 15% percent of the population, followed by Judaism (3%) and Islam (2%).
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Around 1% identify with other Christian denominations.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2010, 91% (526,705) of Baltimore residents five years old and older spoke only English at home.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Other languages, such as African languages, French, and Chinese are spoken by less than 1% of the population.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Once a predominantly industrial town, with an economic base focused on steel processing, shipping, auto manufacturing (General Motors Baltimore Assembly), and transportation, Baltimore experienced deindustrialization, which cost residents tens of thousands of low-skill, high-wage jobs.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore now relies on a low-wage service economy, which accounts for 31% of jobs in the city.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Around the turn of the 20th century, Baltimore was the leading U.S. manufacturer of rye whiskey and straw hats.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] It led in the refining of crude oil, brought to the city by pipeline from Pennsylvania.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In March 2018, Baltimore's unemployment rate was 5.8%.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2012, one quarter of Baltimore residents, and 37% of Baltimore children, lived in poverty.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The city is home to the Johns Hopkins Hospital.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Other large companies in Baltimore include Under Armour, BRT Laboratories, Cordish Company, Legg Mason, McCormick & Company, T.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] A sugar refinery owned by American Sugar Refining is one of Baltimore's cultural icons.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Nonprofits based in Baltimore include Lutheran Services in America, Catholic Relief Services and Jhpiego.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Almost a quarter of the jobs in the Baltimore region were in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics as of mid-2013, a fact attributed in part to the city's extensive undergraduate and graduate schools; maintenance and repair experts were included in this count.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The center of international commerce for the region is the World Trade Center Baltimore, which houses the Maryland Port Administration and U.S. headquarters for major shipping lines.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Among all U.S. ports, Baltimore is ranked 9th for total dollar value of cargo and 13th for cargo tonnage.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2014, cargo moving through the port totaled 29.5 million tons valued at $52.5 billion.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Port of Baltimore generates $3 billion in annual wages and salary, supports 14,630 direct jobs and 108,000 jobs connected to port work, and in 2014 generated more than $300 million in taxes.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The port serves over 50 ocean carriers, making nearly 1,800 annual visits.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Among all U.S. ports, Baltimore is first in handling automobiles, light trucks, farm and construction machinery; and imported forest products, aluminum, and sugar.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Port of Baltimore's cruise industry, which offers year-round trips on several lines, supports over 400 jobs and brings in over $63 million to Maryland's economy annually.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore's history and attractions have made it a popular tourist destination.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] In 2014, the city hosted 24.5 million visitors, who spent $5.2 billion.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Much of the city's tourism centers around the Inner Harbor, with the National Aquarium being Maryland's top tourist destination.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] Baltimore Harbor's restoration has made it "a city of boats", with several historic ships maintained by the Historic Ships in Baltimore organization and open to the public.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p01] The Inner Harbor is also the home port of *Pride of Baltimore II*, the state's "goodwill ambassador" ship and a reconstruction of a famous Baltimore Clipper.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has historically been a working-class port town, sometimes dubbed a "city of neighborhoods".
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It comprises 72 designated historic districts traditionally occupied by distinct ethnic groups.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Further inland, Mount Vernon is the traditional center of cultural and artistic life of the city.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It is home to a distinctive Washington Monument, set atop a hill in a 19th-century urban square, that predates the monument in Washington, D.C. by several decades.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a significant German American population, and was the second-largest port of immigration to the United States behind Ellis Island in New York and New Jersey.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Between 1820 and 1989, almost 2 million migrants—among them German, Polish, English, Irish, Russian, Lithuanian, Greek and Italian—came to Baltimore, mostly between 1861 and 1930.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] By 1913 the city was averaging forty thousand immigrants per year, until World War I closed off the flow.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] A Chinatown dating to at least the 1880s once held some 400 Chinese residents; a local Chinese-American association remains based there.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Beer making thrived in Baltimore from the 1800s to the 1950s, with over 100 breweries in the city's past.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The best remaining examples are the old American Brewery Building on North Gay Street and the National Brewing Company building in Brewer's Hill.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In the 1940s the National Brewing Company introduced the nation's first six-pack; its two most prominent brands were National Bohemian Beer (colloquially "Natty Boh") and Colt 45.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Both are still made today, albeit outside Maryland, and remain local staples whose "Natty Boh" mascot appears on merchandise throughout the area.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Each year the Artscape takes place in the city in the Bolton Hill neighborhood, close to the Maryland Institute College of Art.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Artscape styles itself as the "largest free arts festival in America".
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Each May, the Maryland Film Festival takes place in Baltimore, using all five screens of the historic Charles Theatre as its anchor venue.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Many movies and television shows have been filmed in Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] *Homicide: Life on the Street* was set and filmed in Baltimore, as well as *The Wire.* *House of Cards* and *Veep* are set in Washington, D.C. but filmed in Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has cultural museums in many areas of study.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Museum of Art and the Walters Art Museum are internationally renowned for their collections of art.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Museum of Art has the largest holding of works by Henri Matisse in the world.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The American Visionary Art Museum has been designated by Congress as America's national museum for visionary art.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The National Great Blacks In Wax Museum is the first African American wax museum in the country, featuring more than 150 life-size and lifelike wax figures.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is known for its Maryland blue crabs, crab cake, Old Bay Seasoning, pit beef, and the "chicken box" (chicken wings with french fries).
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The city has many restaurants in or around the Inner Harbor, with Little Italy and Fells Point—home to the country's oldest continuously running tavern, "The Horse You Came in on Saloon"—drawing tourists and locals alike.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Public Market System is the oldest continuously operating public market system in the United States, and Lexington Market, dating to 1782, is among the longest-running in the world.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is also the last place in America with arabbers, vendors who sell produce from horse-drawn carts.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 2015, Zagat ranked Baltimore second on a list of the 17 best food cities in the U.S.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore city, along with its surrounding regions, is home to a unique local dialect known as the Baltimore dialect.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It is part of the larger Mid-Atlantic American English group and is noted to be very similar to the Philadelphia dialect.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The so-called "Bawlmerese" (named so for how locals often pronounce the city as "Bawlmore") accent is known for its characteristic pronunciation of its long "o" vowel, in which an "eh" sound is added before the long "o" sound (/oʊ/ shifts to [ɘʊ], or even [eʊ]).
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It adopts Philadelphia's pattern of the short "a" sound, such that the tensed vowel in words like "bath" or "ask" does not match the more relaxed one in "sad" or "act".
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore native John Waters parodies the city and its dialect extensively in his films.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Most are filmed in Baltimore, including the 1972 cult classic *Pink Flamingos*, as well as *Hairspray* and its Broadway musical remake.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has four state-designated arts and entertainment districts: The Pennsylvania Avenue Black Arts and Entertainment District, Station North Arts and Entertainment District, Highlandtown Arts District, and the Bromo Arts & Entertainment District.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Office of Promotion and the Arts (BOPA), the official city arts council, produces arts programs, manages several facilities, and coordinates major events such as the Inner Harbor's New Year's Eve and July 4 celebrations, Artscape, the Baltimore Book Festival, and the Dr.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Symphony Orchestra is an internationally renowned orchestra, founded in 1916 as a publicly funded municipal organization.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Its most recent music director was Marin Alsop, a protégé of Leonard Bernstein's.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Centerstage is the premier theater company in the city and a regionally well-respected group.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Lyric Opera House is the home of Lyric Opera Baltimore, which operates there as part of the Patricia and Arthur Modell Performing Arts Center.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Shriver Hall Concert Series, founded in 1966, presents classical chamber music and recitals featuring nationally and internationally recognized artists.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Peabody Institute, located in the Mount Vernon neighborhood, is the oldest conservatory of music in the United States.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Established in 1857, it is one of the most prestigious in the world, along with Juilliard, Eastman, and the Curtis Institute.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Morgan State University Choir is one of the nation's most prestigious university choral ensembles.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The city is also home to the Baltimore School for the Arts, a public high school in Mount Vernon nationally recognized for preparing students in music, theatre, dance, and visual arts.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 1981, Baltimore hosted the first International Theater Festival, staging 66 performances of nine shows by international theatre companies; the event proved expensive and moved to Denver the following year.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In June 1986, the 20th Theatre of Nations, sponsored by the International Theatre Institute, was held in Baltimore, the first time it had taken place in the U.S.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a long and storied baseball history, including its distinction as the birthplace of Babe Ruth in 1895.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The original 19th-century Baltimore Orioles (1882–1899) were among the most successful early franchises.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] A short-lived American League Orioles played in 1901–1902 before moving to New York and becoming the New York Yankees, while Ruth played for the minor-league Orioles, who competed locally until 1953.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The team currently known as the Baltimore Orioles has represented Major League Baseball locally since 1954 when the St.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 1995, local player (and later Hall of Famer) Cal Ripken Jr. broke Lou Gehrig's streak of 2,130 consecutive games played, for which Ripken was named Sportsman of the Year by *Sports Illustrated* magazine.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Six former Orioles players, including Ripken (2007), and two of the team's managers have been inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Since 1992, the Orioles' home ballpark has been Oriole Park at Camden Yards, which has been hailed as one of the league's best since it opened.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Before the 1950s, several attempts at a professional football team in Baltimore were blocked by the Washington franchise and its NFL allies.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The first major-league team in the city was the All-America Football Conference (AAFC) Baltimore Colts, which played from 1947 to 1949, joined the NFL for a single year (1950), and then went bankrupt.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 1953, the NFL's Dallas Texans folded.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Its assets and player contracts were purchased by an ownership team headed by Baltimore businessman Carroll Rosenbloom, who moved the team to Baltimore, establishing a new team also named the Baltimore Colts.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] During the 1950s and 1960s, the Colts were one of the NFLs more successful franchises, led by Pro Football Hall of Fame quarterback Johnny Unitas.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Colts advanced to the NFL Championship twice (1958 and 1959) and the Super Bowl twice (1969 and 1971), winning all except Super Bowl III in 1969.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] After the 1983 season, the team left Baltimore for Indianapolis in 1984, where they became the Indianapolis Colts.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The NFL returned to Baltimore when the former Cleveland Browns personnel moved to Baltimore and established the Baltimore Ravens in 1996.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore also hosted a Canadian Football League franchise, the Baltimore Stallions for the 1994 and 1995 seasons.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Following the 1995 season, and ultimate end to the Canadian Football League in the United States experiment, the team was sold and relocated to Montreal.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The first professional sports organization in the United States, The Maryland Jockey Club, was formed in Baltimore in 1743.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Preakness Stakes, the second race in the United States Triple Crown of Thoroughbred Racing, has been held every May at Pimlico Race Course in Baltimore since 1873.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] College lacrosse is a common sport in the spring, as the Johns Hopkins Blue Jays men's lacrosse team has won 44 national championships, the most of any program in history.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In addition, Loyola University won its first men's NCAA lacrosse championship in 2012.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Blast are a professional arena soccer team that play in the Major Arena Soccer League at the SECU Arena on the campus of Towson University.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Blast have won nine championships in various leagues, including the MASL; a previous Blast franchise played in the Major Indoor Soccer League from 1980 to 1992, winning one championship.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Other local clubs have included the semi-professional soccer sides FC Baltimore 1729 (founded 2018 in the National Premier Soccer League) and the Baltimore Bohemians, and Baltimore City F.C., an American Premier Soccer League club playing since 2023 at Utz Field in Patterson Park.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Blues were a semi-professional rugby league club that began competition in the USA Rugby League in 2012.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Grand Prix ran along the streets of downtown's Inner Harbor from 2011 to 2013, hosting the American Le Mans Series and IndyCar Series before being discontinued over scheduling conflicts.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Marathon, the flagship of several races, begins and ends at Camden Yards, winding through neighborhoods including the Inner Harbor, Federal Hill, Fells Point, Canton, and Patterson Park.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore Brigade were an Arena Football League team based in Baltimore that, from 2017 to 2019, played at Royal Farms Arena.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 2019, the team ceased operations along with the rest of the league.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has over 4,900 acres (1,983 ha) of parkland.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore City Department of Recreation and Parks manages the majority of parks and recreational facilities in the city, including Patterson Park, Federal Hill Park, and Druid Hill Park.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Gwynns Falls/Leakin Park, the city's most extensive park, is also the second-largest urban woodland in the nation.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The city is home to Fort McHenry National Monument and Historic Shrine, a coastal star-shaped fort best known for its role in the War of 1812.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] As of 2015, The Trust for Public Land, a national land conservation organization, ranks Baltimore 40th among the 75-largest U.S. cities.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is an independent city, and not part of any county.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] For most governmental purposes under Maryland law, Baltimore City is treated as a county-level entity.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The United States Census Bureau uses counties as the basic unit for presentation of statistical information in the United States, and treats Baltimore as a county equivalent for those purposes.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Hirsch Goldberg, a former press secretary for a mayor of the city, stated in the *Baltimore Sun* that because Baltimore is not in a county, there is no county-wide government that could assist the city, and that the city does not have as much political representation in the Maryland Legislature.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Goldberg argued that the status of not being in a county, along with the total square mileage, which he characterized as small, was damaging the city's fortunes.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has been a Democratic stronghold for over 150 years, with Democrats dominating every level of government.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In virtually all elections, the Democratic primary is the real contest.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] As of the 2020 elections, registered Democrats outnumbered registered Republicans by almost 10-to-1.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] No Republican has been elected to the City Council since 1939.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The city's last Republican mayor, Theodore McKeldin, left office in 1967.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] No Republican candidate since then has received 30 percent or more of the vote.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In the 2016 and 2020 mayoral elections, the Republicans were pushed into third place by write-in and independent candidates, respectively.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The last Republican candidate for president to win the city was Dwight Eisenhower in his successful reelection bid in 1956.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The city hosted the first six Democratic National Conventions, from 1832 through 1852, and hosted the DNC again in 1860, 1872, and 1912.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Brandon Scott is the current mayor of Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] He was elected in 2020 and took office on December 8, 2020.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Scott succeeded Jack Young, who became acting mayor in April 2019 and then mayor upon the resignation of Catherine Pugh, who left office amid a self-dealing book-sales scandal.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Pugh, a Democrat, had won the 2016 election with 57.1% of the vote.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Stephanie Rawlings-Blake, previously City Council President, became mayor in February 2010 upon Dixon's resignation and won a full term in 2011.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Sheila Dixon, Baltimore's first female mayor, had taken office in 2007 after Martin O'Malley became governor; she resigned in 2010 following an embezzlement conviction and an Alford plea to a perjury charge, as Maryland does not allow convicted felons to hold office.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore City Council is made up of 14 members elected from single-member districts and a council president elected at-large.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The council president is *ex officio* mayor pro tempore; if the mayor's office falls vacant, the council president ascends as mayor for the balance of the term.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Grassroots pressure for reform, voiced as Question P, restructured the city council in November 2002, against the will of the mayor, the council president, and the majority of the council.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] A coalition of union and community groups, organized by the Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN), backed the effort.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore City Police Department is the primary law enforcement agency serving Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It began in 1784 as a night watch and day constable system, was reorganized as a city department in 1853, and came under State of Maryland supervision in 1859.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Campus and building security for the city's public schools is provided by the Baltimore City Public Schools Police, established in the 1970s.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 2015, Baltimore agreed to pay $6.4 million to settle civil claims by the family of Freddie Gray, a sum greater than the combined settlements from 120 police brutality and misconduct lawsuits filed from 2011 to 2015.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has had a high violent-crime and homicide rate for decades, even as overall reported crime fell substantially from the mid-1990s to the mid-2010s.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Homicides peaked at 353 in 1993 and reached 344 in 2015, when the city recorded its highest homicide rate because its population had declined.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] After remaining above 300 annually from 2016 through 2022, homicides declined to 263 in 2023 and 200 in 2024.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is protected by the over 1,800 professional firefighters of the Baltimore City Fire Department (BCFD), founded in 1858 to replace the city's warring volunteer companies.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The BCFD operates out of 37 fire stations throughout the city.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Since the legislative redistricting in 2002, Baltimore has had six legislative districts located entirely within its boundaries, giving the city six seats in the 47-member Maryland Senate and 14 in the 141-member Maryland House of Delegates.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] During the previous 10-year period, Baltimore had four legislative districts within the city limits, but four others overlapped the Baltimore County line.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] As of October 2024, all of Baltimore's state senators and delegates were Democrats.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is split between two of the state's eight congressional districts.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Most of the city is included in the 7th district, represented by Kweisi Mfume.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] A sliver of northern Baltimore is located in the 2nd district, represented by Johnny Olszewski.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] A Republican has not represented a significant portion of Baltimore in Congress since John Boynton Philip Clayton Hill represented the 3rd District in 1927, and has not represented any of Baltimore since the Eastern Shore-based 1st District lost its share of Baltimore after the 2000 census.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It was represented by Republican Wayne Gilchrest at the time.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Maryland's former United States senator Ben Cardin is from Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] He was one of three people who, over four decades, represented the 3rd District—long including much of inner Baltimore—before election to the U.S.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Senate, the others being Paul Sarbanes and Barbara Mikulski.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Postal Service's Baltimore Main Post Office is located at 900 East Fayette Street in the Jonestown area.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The national headquarters for the United States Social Security Administration is located in Woodlawn, just outside of Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is the home of numerous places of higher learning, both public and private.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] 100,000 college students from around the country attend Baltimore City's 10 accredited two-year or four-year colleges and universities.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The city's public schools are managed by Baltimore City Public Schools.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Notable among them are Frederick Douglass High School, the second-oldest African American high school in the United States; Baltimore City College, the third-oldest public high school in the nation; and Western High School, the oldest public all-girls school in the nation.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore City College and Baltimore Polytechnic Institute share the nation's second-oldest high school football rivalry.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a higher-than-average percentage of households without a car.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 2015, 30.7 percent of Baltimore households lacked a car, which decreased slightly to 28.9 percent in 2016.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The national average was 8.7 percent in 2016.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore averaged 1.65 cars per household in 2016, compared to a national average of 1.8.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore's highway growth has done much to influence the development of the city and its suburbs.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The first limited-access highway serving Baltimore was the Baltimore–Washington Parkway, which opened in stages between 1950 and 1954; its maintenance is split between the state of Maryland and the National Park Service, and trucks are restricted to its northern part.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Route 1 until Interstate 95 between Baltimore and Washington opened in 1971.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Interstate highways serving Baltimore are I-70, I-83 (the Jones Falls Expressway), I-95, I-395, I-695 (the Baltimore Beltway), I-795 (the Northwest Expressway), I-895 (the Harbor Tunnel Thruway), and I-97.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The city's mainline Interstate highways—I-95, I-83, and I-70—do not directly connect to each other, and in the case of I-70 end at a park and ride lot just inside the city limits, because of freeway revolts in Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] These revolts were led primarily by Barbara Mikulski, a former United States senator for Maryland, which resulted in the abandonment of the original plan.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] There are two tunnels traversing Baltimore Harbor within the city limits: the four-bore Fort McHenry Tunnel (opened in 1985 and serving I-95) and the two-bore Harbor Tunnel (opened in 1957 and serving I-895).
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Until its collapse in March 2024, the Baltimore Beltway crossed south of Baltimore Harbor over the Francis Scott Key Bridge.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Planning for the Baltimore Beltway predates the creation of the Interstate Highway System.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Highways in the city are US 1, which bypasses downtown, and US 40, which crosses downtown from east to west.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Both run along major surface streets, US 40 utilizes a small section of a freeway cancelled in the 1970s in the west side of the city, originally intended for Interstate 170.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] State routes in the city travel along surface streets, with the exception of Maryland Route 295, which carries the Baltimore–Washington Parkway.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Baltimore City Department of Transportation (BCDOT) maintains the city's streets, sidewalks, and alleys, road signs, and street lights, and handles vehicle towing and traffic cameras.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Its responsibilities include the state and U.S. highways and the portions of I-83 and I-70 within the city limits; I-95, I-395, I-695, and I-895 are instead maintained by the Maryland Transportation Authority.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Public transit in Baltimore is mostly provided by the Maryland Transit Administration (abbreviated "MTA Maryland") and Charm City Circulator.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] MTA Maryland operates a comprehensive bus network, including many local, express, and commuter buses.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Charm City Circulator (CCC), a free shuttle bus service operated for the Baltimore City Department of Transportation, began running in the downtown area in January 2010.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Funded partly by an increase in parking fees, it provides free service seven days a week across four color-coded routes linking downtown with Johns Hopkins Hospital, Fells Point, Federal Hill, Harbor East, and Fort McHenry.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a water taxi service, operated by Baltimore Water Taxi.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The water taxi's six routes provide service throughout the city's harbor, and was purchased by Under Armour CEO Kevin Plank's Sagamore Ventures in 2016.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In June 2017, the BaltimoreLink bus network redesign was launched.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The BaltimoreLink redesign consisted of a dozen high frequency, color-coded routes branded CityLink, running every 10 to 15 minutes through downtown Baltimore, along with changes to local and express bus service, rebranded LocalLink and ExpressLink.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is a top destination for Amtrak along the Northeast Corridor, and its Penn Station is one of the busiest in the country—ranked the seventh-busiest U.S. rail station as of 2014.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The corridor approaches from the south through the 1873 Baltimore and Potomac Tunnel, whose 30 mph (50 km/h) limit, sharp curves, and steep grades make it one of the NEC's worst bottlenecks, and from the north through the 1873 Union Tunnel.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Just outside the city, BWI Thurgood Marshall Airport Rail Station is another stop.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Scheduled Amtrak services include the *Acela Express*, *Northeast Regional*, and several long-distance trains such as the *Silver Star*, *Silver Meteor*, *Crescent*, and *Vermonter*.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] MARC commuter rail (the Brunswick, Camden, and Penn lines) connects Camden Station and Penn Station with Washington, D.C.'s Union Station and stops in between; the Penn Line added weekend service in 2013.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is served by two airports, both operated by the Maryland Aviation Administration, which is part of the Maryland Department of Transportation.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore–Washington International Thurgood Marshall Airport, generally known as "BWI", is the main international airport in the Baltimore area.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It lies about 10 miles (16 km) to the south of Baltimore in neighboring Anne Arundel County.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The airport is named after Thurgood Marshall, a Baltimore native who was the first African American to serve on the Supreme Court of the United States.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In terms of passenger traffic, BWI is the 22nd busiest airport in the United States.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] As of 2014, BWI is the largest, by passenger count, of three major airports serving the Baltimore–Washington Metropolitan Area.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It is accessible by I-95 and the Baltimore–Washington Parkway via Interstate 195, the Baltimore Light Rail, and Amtrak and MARC Train at BWI Rail Station.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is also served by Martin State Airport, a general aviation facility, to the northeast in Baltimore County.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Martin State Airport is linked to downtown Baltimore by Maryland Route 150 (Eastern Avenue) and by MARC Train at its own station.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has a comprehensive, signed system of unnumbered bicycle routes, with roads marked by bike lanes, sharrows, or Share the Road signs.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The network continues to expand, with over 140 miles (230 km) of lanes added between 2006 and 2014, and the city has also built bike boulevards, beginning with Guilford Avenue in 2012.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The city has three major trail systems—the Gwynns Falls Trail, the Jones Falls Trail, and the Herring Run Trail—the first two of which carry sections of the East Coast Greenway.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Protected cycle tracks on Maryland Avenue, Mount Royal Avenue, and Monument Street form the backbone of the downtown bicycle network, while the Stony Run Trail follows part of the old Ma and Pa Railroad corridor.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] A 2011 study by Walk Score ranked Baltimore the 14th-most walkable of the fifty largest U.S. cities.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The port was founded in 1706, preceding the founding of Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Maryland colonial legislature made the area near Locust Point as the port of entry for the tobacco trade with England.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Fells Point, the deepest point in the natural harbor, soon became the colony's main ship building center, later on becoming leader in the construction of clipper ships.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] After Baltimore's founding, mills were built behind the wharves, and the California Gold Rush brought orders for fast vessels.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] By the end of the nineteenth century, European ship lines maintained immigrant terminals there, and the Baltimore and Ohio Railroad made the port a major transshipment point.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The port has major roll-on/roll-off and bulk facilities, especially for steel handling.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Water taxis operate in the Inner Harbor.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Governor Ehrlich participated in naming the port after Helen Delich Bentley during the 300th anniversary of the port.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 2007, Duke Realty Corporation began the Chesapeake Commerce Center, a 184-acre (0.74 km2) industrial park on the site of a former General Motors plant in eastern Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The Port of Baltimore is one of two East Coast seaports with a 50-foot (15 m) dredge able to accommodate the largest shipping vessels.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has four water wheel trash interceptors for removing garbage in area waterways.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] One is at the mouth of Jones Falls in Baltimore's Inner Harbor, dubbed "Mr.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Another, "Professor Trash Wheel", was added at Harris Creek in the Canton neighborhood in 2016, with "Captain Trash Wheel" following at Mason Creek in 2018, and "Gwynnda, the Good Wheel of the West" at the mouth of the Gwynns Falls in 2021.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] A February 2015 agreement with a local waste-to-energy plant is believed to make Baltimore the first city to use reclaimed waterway debris to generate electricity.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In August 2010, the National Aquarium assembled, planted, and launched a floating wetland island designed by Biohabitats in Baltimore's Inner Harbor.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Hundreds of years ago, Baltimore's harbor shoreline would have been lined with tidal wetlands.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Biohabitats also developed a concept to transform a dilapidated wharf into a living pier that cleans Harbor water, provides habitat and is an aesthetic attraction.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Currently under design, the top of the pier will become a constructed tidal wetland.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Other projects to improve water quality include the Blue Alleys project, expanded street sweeping, and stream restoration.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Since 1985 the Wheelabrator Baltimore incinerator, formerly known as the Baltimore Refuse Energy Systems Co., has operated as a waste-to-energy incinerator.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The incinerator is a significant source of air pollution to nearby neighborhoods.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Several environmental groups, such as the Environmental Integrity Project, and the Chesapeake Climate Action Network, have been successful in advocating for reinforced pollution monitoring.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The incinerator is the city's single largest standing source of air pollution.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore's main media outlet since 2010 is *The Baltimore Sun*, which was sold by its Baltimore owners in 1986 to the Times Mirror Company, and then bought by the Tribune Company in 2000.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Since the sale, *The Baltimore Sun* prints some local news along with regional and national articles.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The *Baltimore News-American*, another long-running paper that competed with the Sun, ceased publication in 1986.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The city is home to the Baltimore Afro-American, an influential African American newspaper founded in 1892.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 2006, *The Baltimore Examiner* was launched to compete with *The Sun*.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It was part of a national chain that includes *The San Francisco Examiner* and *The Washington Examiner*.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In contrast to the paid subscription *Sun*, *The Examiner* was a free newspaper funded solely by advertisements.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Unable to turn a profit and facing a deep recession, *The Baltimore Examiner* ceased publication on February 15, 2009.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Despite being located 40 miles northeast of Washington, D.C., Baltimore is a major media market in its own right, with all major English language television networks represented in the city.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] WJZ-TV 13 is a CBS owned and operated station, and WBFF 45 (Fox, with MyNetworkTV on DT2) is the flagship of Sinclair Broadcast Group, the second-largest station owner in the country.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Other major television stations in Baltimore include WMAR-TV 2 (ABC), WBAL-TV 11 (NBC), WUTB 24 (Roar), WNUV 54 (CW), and WMPB 67 (PBS).
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore is also served by low-power station WMJF-CD 39 (Ion), which transmits from the campus of Towson University.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Nielsen ranked Baltimore as the 27th-largest television market in 2009.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Arbitron's Fall 2010 rankings identified Baltimore as the 22nd-largest radio market.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Edgar Allan Poe lived in several different cities including Baltimore, which is where he died and was buried.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Several of his works were inspired and written during his time in the city including "MS.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Scott Fitzgerald—who had deep ties to Baltimore as a relative and namesake of Francis Scott Key—published the short story *The Curious Case of Benjamin Button*, about a man born in Baltimore who ages backwards.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Fitzgerald lived in the city for five years in the 1930s, partly so that Zelda could receive psychiatric care at Johns Hopkins and the Sheppard-Pratt Hospital; his first editor was the "Sage of Baltimore", H.L.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Anne Tyler has lived in Baltimore since the late 1960s and is known for her literary realism fiction that emphasizes family life.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] She has written a number of books set locally including *The Accidental Tourist* (1985), *Breathing Lessons* (1988), *Digging To America* (2006) and *A Spool of Blue Thread* (2015).
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 1845, Frederick Douglass published his memoir: *Narrative of the Life of Frederick Douglass, an American Slave*.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Born on the Eastern Shore, Douglass arrived in Baltimore as a child.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] It is where he learned to read and write.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 2008, journalist, novelist and activist Ta-Nehisi Coates published his memoir of growing up in West Baltimore: *The Beautiful Struggle.* Coates writes of his challenging relationship with his father, troubled experiences in local schools and the street crime and drug epidemic of the 1990s.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Barry Levinson is a film maker and a native Baltimorean.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Several of his films pay homage to his upbringing in an immigrant family in the city: *Diner* (1982), *Tin Men* (1987), *Avalon* (1990), and *Liberty Heights* (1999).
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Another Baltimore filmmaker, John Waters, began his career making experimental art films in the city including *Roman Candies* and *Mondo Trasho*.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] As his audience and film budgets expanded, Waters continued to set his films in Baltimore and to premier them at the Senator Theater.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Waters has continued to live in Baltimore and remains active in the local arts community.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The television representations of Baltimore often involve crime or law enforcement.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] From 1993 to 1998, the police procedural drama *Homicide: Life on the Street* aired with favorable reviews but low ratings.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Several episodes of the *X-Files* (1993–2002) took place in Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] *The Corner* (2000) is a mini-series based on a true story of people living amid the open air drug markets of West Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] The most known series set in Baltimore is *The Wire* (2002–2008), which was well-received and depicts the city as a war zone between drug trade and the police.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] In 2022, the limited drama series *We Own This City* premiered, starring Jon Bernthal and native Baltimorean Josh Charles.
[src:ernst-cloos/baltimore-p02] Baltimore has ten sister cities, as designated by Sister Cities International.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] A **biplane** is a fixed-wing aircraft with two main wings stacked one above the other.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The first powered, controlled aeroplane to fly, the Wright Flyer, used a biplane wing arrangement, as did many aircraft in the early years of aviation.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] While a biplane wing structure has a structural advantage over a monoplane, it produces more drag than a monoplane wing.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Improved structural techniques, better materials and higher speeds made the biplane configuration obsolete for most purposes by the late 1930s.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Biplanes offer several advantages over conventional cantilever monoplane designs: they permit lighter wing structures, low wing loading and smaller span for a given wing area.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] However, interference between the airflow over each wing increases drag substantially, and biplanes generally need extensive bracing, which causes additional drag.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Biplanes are distinguished from tandem wing arrangements, where the wings are placed forward and aft, instead of above and below.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The term is also occasionally used in biology, to describe the wings of some flying animals.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] In a biplane aircraft, two wings are placed one above the other.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Each provides part of the lift, although they are not able to produce twice as much lift as a single wing of similar size and shape because the upper and the lower are working on nearly the same portion of the atmosphere and thus interfere with each other's behaviour.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] In a biplane configuration with no stagger from the upper wing to the lower wing, the lift coefficient is reduced by 10 to 15 percent compared to that of a monoplane using the same airfoil and aspect ratio.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The lower wing is usually attached to the fuselage, while the upper wing is raised above the fuselage with an arrangement of cabane struts, although other arrangements have been used.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Either or both of the main wings can support ailerons, while flaps are more usually positioned on the lower wing.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Bracing is nearly always added between the upper and lower wings, in the form of interplane struts positioned symmetrically on either side of the fuselage and bracing wires to keep the structure from flexing, where the wings are not themselves cantilever structures.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The primary advantage of the biplane over a monoplane is its ability to combine greater stiffness with lower weight.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Stiffness requires structural depth and where early monoplanes had to have this provided with external bracing, the biplane naturally has a deep structure and is therefore easier to make both light and strong.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Rigging wires on non-cantilevered monoplanes are at a much sharper angle, thus providing less tension to ensure stiffness of the outer wing.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] On a biplane, since the angles are closer to the ideal of being in direct line with the forces being opposed, the overall structure can then be made stiffer.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Because of the reduced stiffness, wire braced monoplanes often had multiple sets of flying and landing wires where a biplane could easily be built with one bay, with one set of landing and flying wires.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The extra drag from the wires was not enough to offset the aerodynamic disadvantages from having two airfoils interfering with each other however.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Strut braced monoplanes were tried but none of them were successful, not least due to the drag from the number of struts used.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The structural forces acting on the spars of a biplane wing tend to be lower as they are divided between four spars rather than two, so the wing can use less material to obtain the same overall strength and is therefore lighter.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] A given area of wing also tends to be shorter, reducing bending moments on the spars, which then allow them to be more lightly built as well.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The biplane does however need extra struts to maintain the gap between the wings, which add both weight and drag.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The low power supplied by the engines available in the first years of aviation limited aeroplanes to fairly low speeds.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] This required an even lower stalling speed, which in turn required a low wing loading, combining both large wing area with light weight.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Obtaining a large enough wing area without the wings being long, and thus dangerously flexible was more readily accomplished with a biplane.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The smaller biplane wing allows greater maneuverability.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Following World War I, this helped extend the era of the biplane and, despite the performance disadvantages, most fighter aircraft were biplanes as late as the mid-1930s.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Specialist sports aerobatic biplanes are still made in small numbers.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Biplanes suffer aerodynamic interference between the two planes when the high pressure air under the top wing and the low pressure air above the lower wing cancel each other out.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] This means that a biplane does not in practice obtain twice the lift of the similarly sized monoplane.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The farther apart the wings are spaced the less the interference, but the spacing struts must be longer, and the gap must be extremely large to reduce it appreciably.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The default design for a biplane has the wings positioned directly one above the other.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Moving the upper wing forward relative to the lower one is called positive stagger or, more often, simply stagger.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] It can increase lift and reduce drag by reducing the aerodynamic interference effects between the two wings by a small degree, but more often was used to improve access to the cockpit.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Common examples include the de Havilland Tiger Moth, Bücker Bü 131 Jungmann and Travel Air 2000.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Alternatively, the lower wing can instead be moved ahead of the upper wing, giving negative stagger, and similar benefits.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] This is usually done in a given design for structural reasons, or to improve visibility.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Examples of negative stagger include the Sopwith Dolphin, Breguet 14 and Beechcraft Staggerwing.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] However, positive (forward) stagger is much more common.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The space enclosed by a set of interplane struts is called a *bay* (much as the architectural form is used), hence a biplane or triplane with one set of such struts connecting the wings on each side of the aircraft is a *single-bay biplane*.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] This provided sufficient strength for smaller aircraft such as the First World War-era Fokker D.VII fighter and the Second World War de Havilland Tiger Moth basic trainer.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The larger two-seat Curtiss JN-4 Jenny is a *two bay biplane*, the extra bay being necessary as overlong bays are prone to flexing and can fail.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The SPAD S.XIII fighter, while appearing to be a two bay biplane, has only one bay, but has the midpoints of the rigging braced with additional struts; however, these are not structurally contiguous from top to bottom wing.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The Sopwith 1½ Strutter has a W shape cabane, however as it does not connect the wings to each other, it does not add to the number of bays.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Large transport and bombing biplanes often needed still more bays to provide sufficient strength.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] These are often referred to as *multi-bay biplanes*.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] A small number of biplanes, such as the Zeppelin-Lindau D.I have no interplane struts and are referred to as being *strutless*.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Because most biplanes do not have cantilever structures, they require rigging wires to maintain their rigidity.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Early aircraft used simple wire (either braided or plain), however during the First World War, the British Royal Aircraft Factory developed airfoil section wire named RAFwire in an effort to both increase the strength and reduce the drag.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Four types of wires are used in the biplane wing structure.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Drag wires inside the wings prevent the wings from being folded back against the fuselage, running inside a wing bay from the forward inboard corner to the rear outboard corner.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Anti-drag wires prevent the wings from moving forward when the aircraft stops and run the opposite direction to the drag wires.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Both of these are usually hidden within the wings, and if the structure is sufficiently stiff otherwise, may be omitted in some designs.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Indeed, many early aircraft relied on the fabric covering of the wing to provide this rigidity, until higher speeds and forces made this inadequate.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Externally, lift wires prevent the wings from folding up, and run from the underside of the outer wing to the lower wing root.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Conversely, landing wires prevent the wings from sagging, and resist the forces when an aircraft is landing, and run from the upper wing centre section to outboard on the lower wings.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Additional drag and anti-drag wires may be used to brace the cabane struts which connect the fuselage to the wings, and interplane struts, which connect the upper and lower wings together.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The *sesquiplane* is a type of biplane where one wing (usually the lower) is significantly smaller than the other.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The word, from Latin, means "one-and-a-half wings".
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The arrangement can reduce drag and weight while retaining the biplane's structural advantages.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The lower wing may have a significantly shorter span, or a reduced chord.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Examples include the series of Nieuport military aircraft—from the Nieuport 10 through to the Nieuport 27 which formed the backbone of the Allied air forces between 1915 and 1917.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The Albatros D.III and D.V, which had also copied the general layout from Nieuport, similarly provided the backbone of the German forces during the First World War.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The Albatros sesquiplanes were widely acclaimed by their aircrews for their maneuverability and high rate of climb.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] During interwar period, the sesquiplane configuration continued to be popular, with numerous types such as the Nieuport-Delage NiD 42/52/62 series, Fokker C.Vd & e, and Potez 25, all serving across a large number of air forces.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] In the general aviation sector, aircraft such as the Waco Custom Cabin series proved to be relatively popular.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The Saro Windhover was a sesquiplane with the upper wing smaller than the lower, which was a much rarer configuration than the reverse.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The Pfalz D.III also featured a somewhat unusual sesquiplane arrangement, possessing a more substantial lower wing with two spars that eliminated the flutter problems encountered by single-spar sesquiplanes.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The stacking of wing planes was suggested by Sir George Cayley in 1843.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Hiram Maxim adopted the idea for his steam-powered test rig, which lifted off but was held down by safety rails, in 1894.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Otto Lilienthal designed and flew two different biplane hang gliders in 1895, though he is better known for his monoplanes.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] By 1896 a group of young men in the United States, led by Octave Chanute, were flying hang gliders including biplanes and concluded that the externally braced biplane offered better prospects for powered flight than the monoplane.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] In 1903, the *Wright Flyer* biplane became the first successful powered aeroplane.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The French were also introducing the Morane-Saulnier AI, a strut-braced parasol monoplane, although the type was quickly relegated to the advanced trainer role following the resolution of structural issues.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Sesquiplane types, which were biplanes with abbreviated lower wings such as the French Nieuport 17 and German Albatros D.III, offered lower drag than a conventional biplane while being stronger than a monoplane.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] During the Interwar period, numerous biplane airliners were introduced.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The British de Havilland Dragon was a particularly successful aircraft, a straightforward design which could carry six passengers on busy routes, such as London-Paris services.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] During early August 1934, one such aircraft, named *Trail of the Caribou*, performed the first non-stop flight between the Canadian mainland and Britain in 30 hours 55 minutes, although the intended target for this long-distance flight had originally been Baghdad, Iraq.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Despite its relative success, British production of the Dragon was quickly ended in favour of the more powerful and elegant de Havilland Dragon Rapide, which had been specifically designed to be a faster and more comfortable successor to the Dragon.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] As the available engine power and speed increased, the drag penalty of external bracing increasingly limited aircraft performance.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] To fly faster, it would be necessary to reduce external bracing to create an aerodynamically clean design; however, early cantilever designs were either too weak or too heavy.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The 1917 Junkers J.I sesquiplane utilized corrugated aluminum for all flying surfaces, with a minimum of struts; however, it was relatively easy to damage the thin metal skin and required careful handling by ground crews.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The 1918 Zeppelin-Lindau D.I fighter was an all-metal stressed-skin monocoque fully cantilevered biplane, but its arrival had come too late to see combat use in the conflict.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] By the 1930s, biplanes had reached their performance limits, and monoplanes become increasingly predominant, particularly in continental Europe where monoplanes had been increasingly common from the end of World War I.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] At the start of World War II, several air forces still had biplane combat aircraft in front line service but they were no longer competitive, and most were used in niche roles, such as training or shipboard operation, until shortly after the end of the war.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The British Gloster Gladiator biplane, the Italian Fiat CR.42 Falco and Soviet I-153 sesquiplane fighters were all still operational after 1939.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] According to aviation author Gianni Cattaneo, the CR.42 was able to achieve success in the defensive night fighter role against RAF bombers that were striking industrial targets throughout northern Italy.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The British Fleet Air Arm operated the Fairey Swordfish torpedo bomber from its aircraft carriers, and used the type in the anti-submarine warfare role until the end of the conflict, largely due to their ability to operate from the relatively compact decks of escort carriers.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Its low stall speed and inherently tough design made it ideal for operations even in the often severe mid-Atlantic weather conditions.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] By the end of the conflict, the Swordfish held the distinction of having caused the destruction of a greater tonnage of Axis shipping than any other Allied aircraft.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Both the German Heinkel He 50 and the Soviet Polikarpov Po-2 were used with relative success in the night ground attack role throughout the Second World War.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] In the case of the Po-2, production of the aircraft continued even after the end of the conflict, not ending until around 1952.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] A significant number of Po-2s were fielded by the Korean People's Air Force during the Korean War, inflicting serious damage during night raids on United Nations bases.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The Po-2 is also the only biplane to be credited with a documented jet-kill, as one Lockheed F-94 Starfire was lost while slowing down to 161 km/h (100 mph) – below its stall speed – during an intercept in order to engage the low flying Po-2.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Later biplane trainers included the de Havilland Tiger Moth in the Royal Air Force (RAF), Royal Canadian Air Force (RCAF) and others and the Stampe SV.4, which saw service postwar in the French and Belgian Air Forces.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The Stearman PT-13 was widely used by the United States Army Air Force (USAAF) while the US Navy operated the Naval Aircraft Factory N3N.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] In later civilian use in the US, the Stearman became particularly associated with stunt flying such as wing-walking, and with crop dusting, where its compactness worked well at low levels, where it had to dodge obstacles.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Modern biplane designs still exist in specialist roles such as aerobatics and agricultural aircraft with the competition aerobatics role and format for such a biplane well-defined by the mid-1930s by the Udet U 12 Flamingo and Waco Taperwing.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The Pitts Special dominated aerobatics for many years after World War II and is still in production.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The vast majority of biplane designs have been fitted with reciprocating engines.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Exceptions include the Antonov An-3 and WSK-Mielec M-15 Belphegor, fitted with turboprop and turbofan engines respectively.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Some older biplane designs, such as the Grumman Ag Cat are available in upgraded versions with turboprop engines.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The two most produced biplane designs were the 1913 British Avro 504 of which 11,303 were built, and the 1928 Soviet Polikarpov Po-2 of which over 20,000 were built, with the Po-2 being the direct replacement for the Soviet copy of the Avro 504.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The Antonov An-2 was very successful too, with more than 18,000 built.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Although most ultralights are monoplanes, the low speeds and simple construction involved have inspired a small number of biplane ultralights, such as Larry Mauro's *Easy Riser* (1975–).
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Mauro also made a version powered with solar cells driving an electric motor called the Solar Riser.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Mauro's *Easy Riser* was used by "Father Goose", Bill Lishman.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] Other biplane ultralights include the Belgian-designed Aviasud Mistral, the German FK12 Comet (1997–), the Lite Flyer Biplane, the Sherwood Ranger, and the Murphy Renegade.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] The feathered dinosaur *Microraptor gui* glided, and perhaps even flew, on four wings, which may have been configured in a staggered sesquiplane arrangement.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] This was made possible by the presence of flight feathers on both forelimbs and hindlimbs, with the feathers on the forelimbs opening to a greater span.
[src:ernst-cloos/biplane] It has been suggested that the hind limbs could not have opened out sideways but in flight would have hung below and slightly behind the fore limbs.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] Bruno Sander, whose father was a public prosecutor, spent his boyhood in what was then Bozen in the Austro-Hungarian Empire.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] After graduating from secondary school and successfully completing in 1902 his *Matura* in Innsbruck, he studied zoology, mineralogy, botany, physics, and mathematics at the University of Innsbruck.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] There he received in 1907 his doctorate in geology with a study on granites in the region near Brixen in the Sarntal Alps.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] His doctoral dissertation, supervised by Josef Blaas (1851–1936), is entitled *Geologische Beschreibung des Brixner Granits*.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] Sander worked as an academic assistant from 1907 to 1909 at TH Wien and from 1909 to 1913 at the University of Innsbruck, where he completed his habilitation in 1912.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] Beginning in 1913 he was employed at Vienna's *Geologischen Reichsanstalt*, where he worked on geological mapping of South Tyrol.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] During his military service, he was a commissioned officer with the title *Lagerstättenebegutacher* (mineral deposit surveyor) under the command of *K.u.K.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] Part of his duty was in 1917–1918 investigating bituminous marl in the mountains of Bulgaria and Turkey.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] From the end of WW I until 1919 he was in a prisoner-of-war camp in Turkey.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] After the dissolution of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, he returned to his prewar employment in Vienna, where the *Geologischen Reichsanstalt* was renamed the *Geologischen Staatsanstalt*.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] In 1921 Sander was a candidate in the competition for the geology professorship at the University of Innsbruck, but that competition was won by Raimund von Klebelsberg (1886–1967).
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] On the 1st of October 1922, Sander was appointed to the University of Innsbruck's professorial chair of mineralogy and petrography — overcoming the strong resistance against Sander's appointment from the “Vienna School” around Friedrich Johann Karl Becke.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] He was a professor of mineralogy and petrography at the University of Innsbruck from 1922 to 1955, when he retired as professor emeritus.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] Sander became known as the founder of an internationally renowned "Innsbruck school of mineralogy and geology" with branches worldwide.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] Sander's 1-volume (1930) *Gefügekunde der Gesteine* (Structural Science of Rocks) and his 2-volume (1948 & 1950) *Einführung in die Gefügekunde geologischer Körper* (Introduction to the Structural Science of Geological Bodies) both became international standard works.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] He is considered a pioneer of geological-mineralogical structural science with applications in rock mechanics and engineering geology.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] According to Eleanora Bliss Knopf, Sander's 1911 paper *Über Zusammenhänge zwischen Teilbewegung und Gefüge in Gesteinen* is a "milestone in petrology".
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] A central idea in Sander's research is that the symmetries of geological bodies, both macroscopic and microscopic, reflect various symmetries of the depositing media that created the deposit in which the geological bodies are located.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] In addition to his work as a geologist, he was also a writer who published under the pseudonym Anton Santer.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] He belonged to the Brenner group before WW I and from 1919 to 1926 regularly published poems in their magazine *Der Brenner*.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] He also published as Anton Santer in the magazines *Wort im Gebirge* and *Seefelder Zeitung*.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] Sander was awarded in 1950 the Gustav Steinmann Medal, in 1957 the Penrose Medal, and in 1964 the German Mineralogical Society's Abraham Gottlob Werner Medal.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] In 1956, he received an International Feltrinelli Prize, the Austrian Mineralogical Society's Friedrich Becke Medal, and the Belgian Geological Society's André Dumont Medal.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] In 1958 the Austrian Geological Society appointed him an honorary member and awarded him the Eduard Sueß Medal.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] He received honorary doctorates from the University of Göttingen (1937) and the University of Vienna (1959).
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] He was elected in 1936 a member of the Leopoldina and in 1966 a member of the United States National Academy of Sciences.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] He was a member of the Austrian Academy of Sciences (corresponding member since 1940 and full member since 1944), as well as the academies of sciences in Bologna (1942), Uppsala (1947), and Berlin (1950).
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] He received in 1955 the Ring of Honor of the city of Innsbruck, in 1959 the Austrian Decoration of Honor for Science and Art, and in 1967 the Decoration of Honor of the State of Tyrol.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] Waldemar Berdesinski named the mineral sanderite after him in 1952.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] The building of the Faculty of Earth and Atmospheric Sciences at the University of Innsbruck was named after Bruno Sander.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] He is also the namesake of the Sander Pass in Antarctica.
[src:ernst-cloos/bruno-sander] The University of Innsbruck stores his fonds in the Brenner archive.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Ernst Cloos, the younger brother of the well-known geologist Hans Cloos (1885–1951), grew up in Cologne and Freiburg.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] At age 14 he was sent to Switzerland to study at the Swiss *Hermann Lietz-Schule*, where he excelled as a student.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] At age 17 he volunteered for Germany military service in WW I.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] He became the pilot of an observation plane.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] On patrol over France near the Swiss border, his biplane was severely damaged by machine-gun fire from four enemy aircraft.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Cloos managed to crash-land in Switzerland but the observer in his biplane was killed.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] The bullet-riddled biplane was put into a Swiss museum.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] At the end of WW I, Cloos was released from internment in Switzerland and began the study of biology at the University of Freiburg.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] He soon decided to study geology instead of biology and transferred to the University of Breslau, where his brother Hans was a professor of geology.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] In 1923 Ernst Cloos received his doctorate with a dissertation on the granites and gneisses of Bohemia.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] The dissertation is based upon research using methods of granite tectonics pioneered by Hans Cloos.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] At Breslau, Ernst met a classmate, Robert Balk (1899–1955), who became a lifelong friend of the Cloos brothers and later became a professor of geology in the USA.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] After completing his doctorate, Ernst Cloos worked with Hans Stille in Göttingen.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] A possible assistant position was not funded because of severe financial problems during the inflationary period of the Weimar Republic.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Ernst Cloos worked as exploration seismologist for Ludger Mintrop's Seismos company on the Gulf Coast of Texas and Louisiana and later in the deserts of Iraq.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] In 1930 Ernst Cloos received a research grant from the German government to apply the methods of granite tectonics in the Sierra Nevada.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] This research made him known in the USA.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] In 1931 he received a teaching position as a lecturer at Johns Hopkins University, where he began to work on the geology of the Appalachian Mountains in Maryland.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] He used his brother's methods from granite tectonics and new methods in structural petrology (petrofabric analysis) introduced by Bruno Sander.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Cloos also learned petrographic methods that had been established at Johns Hopkins University since the professorship there of George Huntington Williams (1856–1894).
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Cloos taught himself by using notebooks and collections of rocks and thin sections made by Williams.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Cloos preferred to give his lectures in the form of field trips.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] He and his students did tectonic experiments with clay models.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] At Johns Hopkins University, he became in 1937 an associate professor and in 1941 a full professor.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] From 1952 to 1963 he chaired the geology department — during those years he recruited Francis J.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Cloos retired as professor emeritus in 1968 but remained active in field trips and research.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Cloos was elected in 1950 a member of the National Academy of Sciences and in 1954 a member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] From 1951 to 1954 he chaired the Geology and Geography Division of the National Research Council — during those years he spent almost every Friday in Washington, DC.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] For the academic year 1953–1954 he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] He was elected a foreign member of the Finnish Academy of Sciences.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] For the academic year 1955–1956 he was a Guggenheim Fellow.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] In 1968 he received the Gustav Steinmann Medal.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] He was married in 1923 to Margaret Spemann, the daughter of his Freiburg biology professor Hans Spemann.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Margaret Cloos (born in 1898) became an active member of the Quakers in Baltimore.
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Ernst and Margaret Cloos were the parents of two daughters, Gisela (born in 1928) and Veronica (born in 1931).
[src:ernst-cloos/ernst-cloos] Gisela Cloos married the geologist William R.
